{"title_page": "Monmouth Methodist Church", "text_new": "{{Infobox church\n| name             = Monmouth Methodist Church\n| fullname         =\n| image            = Methodist Chapel, 1837 (geograph 5445975).jpg\n| imagesize        =\n| caption          =\n| denomination     = [[Methodist]]\n| diocese          =\n| parish           =\n| division         =\n| subdivision      =\n| founded date     =\n| founder          =\n| architect        = [[George Vaughan Maddox]]\n| style            = [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]]\n| years built = {{Start date|1837}}\n| heritage designation = [[Grade II*]] listed\n| dedicated date   =\n| minister         = Rev Ruth Lownsbrough\n| country          = [[Wales]]\n| osgridref        = {{gbmappingsmall|SO 5094 1295}}\n| coordinates      = {{coord|51.8126|N|2.7117|W|type:landmark_region:GB-MON|display=inline,title}}\n|location          = [[St James Street, Monmouth]], [[Monmouthshire]] NP25 3DL\n| website          = {{URL|monmouthmethodist.org.uk}}\n}}\n'''Monmouth Methodist Church''' is located in [[Monmouth]], south east [[Wales]].  It is set well back from [[St James Street, Monmouth|St James Street]] between buildings. Designed by [[George Vaughan Maddox]] and built in 1837, it retains its original galleries, organ loft and sophisticated pulpit.<ref name=mmc>{{cite web|title=Monmouth Methodist Church|url=http://www.monmouthmethodist.org.uk/contents.html|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn common with many non-conformist places of worship in the town built when town authority lay very much with the established church, it was deliberately set back behind the houses to avoid making too prominent a challenge to the established order. This is one of 24 buildings on the [[Monmouth Heritage Trail]] and is [[Grade II*]] listed.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-2342-wesleyan-methodist-chapel-monmouth |title=Wesleyan Methodist Chapel \u2013 Monmouth \u2013 Monmouthshire \u2013 Wales |publisher=British Listed Buildings |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the eighteenth century the new [[Methodist]]s were challenging the presumption of the established churches in Monmouth. Visiting Methodist ministers were stoned and abused by unruly crowds who were encouraged by the churchwardens and gentlefolk.<ref>Bold, Rev. W. E. (1987), ''Methodism and its Beginnings in Monmouth'', Monmouth Methodist Church</ref> They were sometimes seriously injured \u2013 a preacher was killed by a blow in an open-air service near [[Hay-on-Wye]] in 1840. They persevered however and established their first chapel in Inch Lane, now called Bell Lane, a narrow alley off Church Street. [[John Wesley]] came to preach in the town, firstly in 1779, and four more times in later years, and a larger chapel was built in Weirhead Street as [[Wesleyanism|Wesleyan Methodism]] grew.\n\nFinally, as this chapel proved too small, the present church was designed by [[George Vaughan Maddox]], a local architect who had worked on [[The Hendre]].<ref name=golf>{{cite web|title=The History of The Rolls at Monmouth Golf Club|url=http://www.therollsgolfclub.co.uk/history.html|publisher=Rolls Golf Club|accessdate=17 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103003400/http://www.therollsgolfclub.co.uk/history.html#|archive-date=2007-01-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> The 340 seated church with its impressive fa\u00e7ade was built in 1837.<ref>Newman, John (2000) ''The Buildings of Wales: Gwent/Monmouthshire''. Penguin Books {{ISBN|0-14-071053-1}}</ref> Maddox included [[Ionic order|Ionic]] [[wikt:pilasters|pilasters]] with round-headed [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] windows on the first floor but with triangular window heads on the ground floor, and a fine [[wikt:pediment|pediment]] over all. The church is enhanced by the later Ionic porch. The [[box pews]] allow 340 worshippers in sit in three sections below and in a [[Minstrels' gallery|gallery]] that follows three sides of the interior. The pulpit was much higher than it appears today; it was lowered in 1885 while the floor was raised by two feet. As a consequence, the internal columns bases are not visible as they are covered by the raised floor.\n\n[[File:Peter Mackenzie.jpg|thumb|left|The Reverend Peter Mackenzie (1824\u20131895)]]\nThe Reverend Peter Mackenzie was employed as preacher and he drew a large following; he had a personal relationship with many Methodists, whilst his sermons were filled with \"grotesque descriptions and extremely funny stories\".<ref name=dawson>{{cite book|last=Dawson|first=Joseph|title=Peter Mackenzie, his life and labours (esp. p. 141)|year=1896|url=http://www.ebooksread.com/authors-eng/joseph-dawson/peter-mackenzie-his-life-and-labours-ala/page-9-peter-mackenzie-his-life-and-labours-ala.shtml}}</ref> Mackenzie arrived from [[Burnley]], [[Lancashire]], and lived at [[Coleford, Gloucestershire|Coleford]] with his wife and two children using a donkey to travel around the circuit. A lady visitor, Mrs Bullock, commented whilst waiting for the minister to arrive for the service that she would buy an organ if ever the church was full. The minister arrived and immediately the church had reached its capacity. True to her word an organ was purchased and installed in celebration of this achievement.<ref name=dawson/> This church is considered to be one of the most architecturally distinguished Methodist chapels in South Wales with an interior that reflects its purpose and design. According to the local [[Pevsner Architectural Guides|Pevsner architectural guide]]:<ref name=newman>John Newman, ''The Buildings of Wales: Gwent/Monmouthshire'', Penguin Books, 2000, {{ISBN|0-14-071053-1}}, p. 399</ref> \"The interior, quite exceptionally for an early C19 chapel, is a coherent piece of considered architecture.\"  The church as a whole is described as \"a most satisfying work.\"<ref name=newman/>\n\n==The church today==\nThe church has morning and evening services every week with a family service every month.<ref name=guide>{{cite web|title=Monmouth Town Guide|url=http://www.visitwyevalley.com/download/downloads/id/67/monmouth_town_guide_20112012|publisher=Monmouth Town Council|accessdate=10 December 2011}}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Monmouth church is part of the Newport and Lower Wye Circuit that includes other Methodist churches at [[Trellech]], [[Broadoak, Gloucestershire|Broadoak]], [[Llancloudy]] and [[Wonastow|Gwern-y-Saint]].<ref name=mess>{{cite journal|title=The Messenger|date=Oct\u2013Nov 2011|url=http://www.monmouthmethodist.org.uk/Messenger/MessengerOctNov11.pdf}}</ref><ref>[http://www.monmouthmethodist.org.uk/Messenger/MessengerOctNov11.pdf]</ref>\nThe church also is directly in front of another well known nonce group the Sturt Bennet household with ring leader Barney Sturt Bennet.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Buildings in Monmouth}}\n\n[[Category:Methodist churches in Wales]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Monmouth, Wales]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed churches in Monmouthshire]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical architecture in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox church\n| name             = Monmouth Methodist Church\n| fullname         =\n| image            = Methodist Chapel, 1837 (geograph 5445975).jpg\n| imagesize        =\n| caption          =\n| denomination     = [[Methodist]]\n| diocese          =\n| parish           =\n| division         =\n| subdivision      =\n| founded date     =\n| founder          =\n| architect        = [[George Vaughan Maddox]]\n| style            = [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]]\n| years built = {{Start date|1837}}\n| heritage designation = [[Grade II*]] listed\n| dedicated date   =\n| minister         = Rev Ruth Lownsbrough\n| country          = [[Wales]]\n| osgridref        = {{gbmappingsmall|SO 5094 1295}}\n| coordinates      = {{coord|51.8126|N|2.7117|W|type:landmark_region:GB-MON|display=inline,title}}\n|location          = [[St James Street, Monmouth]], [[Monmouthshire]] NP25 3DL\n| website          = {{URL|monmouthmethodist.org.uk}}\n}}\n'''Monmouth Methodist Church''' is located in [[Monmouth]], south east [[Wales]].  It is set well back from [[St James Street, Monmouth|St James Street]] between buildings. Designed by [[George Vaughan Maddox]] and built in 1837, it retains its original galleries, organ loft and sophisticated pulpit.<ref name=mmc>{{cite web|title=Monmouth Methodist Church|url=http://www.monmouthmethodist.org.uk/contents.html|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn common with many non-conformist places of worship in the town built when town authority lay very much with the established church, it was deliberately set back behind the houses to avoid making too prominent a challenge to the established order. This is one of 24 buildings on the [[Monmouth Heritage Trail]] and is [[Grade II*]] listed.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-2342-wesleyan-methodist-chapel-monmouth |title=Wesleyan Methodist Chapel \u2013 Monmouth \u2013 Monmouthshire \u2013 Wales |publisher=British Listed Buildings |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the eighteenth century the new [[Methodist]]s were challenging the presumption of the established churches in Monmouth. Visiting Methodist ministers were stoned and abused by unruly crowds who were encouraged by the churchwardens and gentlefolk.<ref>Bold, Rev. W. E. (1987), ''Methodism and its Beginnings in Monmouth'', Monmouth Methodist Church</ref> They were sometimes seriously injured \u2013 a preacher was killed by a blow in an open-air service near [[Hay-on-Wye]] in 1840. They persevered however and established their first chapel in Inch Lane, now called Bell Lane, a narrow alley off Church Street. [[John Wesley]] came to preach in the town, firstly in 1779, and four more times in later years, and a larger chapel was built in Weirhead Street as [[Wesleyanism|Wesleyan Methodism]] grew.\n\nFinally, as this chapel proved too small, the present church was designed by [[George Vaughan Maddox]], a local architect who had worked on [[The Hendre]].<ref name=golf>{{cite web|title=The History of The Rolls at Monmouth Golf Club|url=http://www.therollsgolfclub.co.uk/history.html|publisher=Rolls Golf Club|accessdate=17 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103003400/http://www.therollsgolfclub.co.uk/history.html#|archive-date=2007-01-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> The 340 seated church with its impressive fa\u00e7ade was built in 1837.<ref>Newman, John (2000) ''The Buildings of Wales: Gwent/Monmouthshire''. Penguin Books {{ISBN|0-14-071053-1}}</ref> Maddox included [[Ionic order|Ionic]] [[wikt:pilasters|pilasters]] with round-headed [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] windows on the first floor but with triangular window heads on the ground floor, and a fine [[wikt:pediment|pediment]] over all. The church is enhanced by the later Ionic porch. The [[box pews]] allow 340 worshippers in sit in three sections below and in a [[Minstrels' gallery|gallery]] that follows three sides of the interior. The pulpit was much higher than it appears today; it was lowered in 1885 while the floor was raised by two feet. As a consequence, the internal columns bases are not visible as they are covered by the raised floor.\n\n[[File:Peter Mackenzie.jpg|thumb|left|The Reverend Peter Mackenzie (1824\u20131895)]]\nThe Reverend Peter Mackenzie was employed as preacher and he drew a large following; he had a personal relationship with many Methodists, whilst his sermons were filled with \"grotesque descriptions and extremely funny stories\".<ref name=dawson>{{cite book|last=Dawson|first=Joseph|title=Peter Mackenzie, his life and labours (esp. p. 141)|year=1896|url=http://www.ebooksread.com/authors-eng/joseph-dawson/peter-mackenzie-his-life-and-labours-ala/page-9-peter-mackenzie-his-life-and-labours-ala.shtml}}</ref> Mackenzie arrived from [[Burnley]], [[Lancashire]], and lived at [[Coleford, Gloucestershire|Coleford]] with his wife and two children using a donkey to travel around the circuit. A lady visitor, Mrs Bullock, commented whilst waiting for the minister to arrive for the service that she would buy an organ if ever the church was full. The minister arrived and immediately the church had reached its capacity. True to her word an organ was purchased and installed in celebration of this achievement.<ref name=dawson/> This church is considered to be one of the most architecturally distinguished Methodist chapels in South Wales with an interior that reflects its purpose and design. According to the local [[Pevsner Architectural Guides|Pevsner architectural guide]]:<ref name=newman>John Newman, ''The Buildings of Wales: Gwent/Monmouthshire'', Penguin Books, 2000, {{ISBN|0-14-071053-1}}, p. 399</ref> \"The interior, quite exceptionally for an early C19 chapel, is a coherent piece of considered architecture.\"  The church as a whole is described as \"a most satisfying work.\"<ref name=newman/>\n\n==The church today==\nThe church has morning and evening services every week with a family service every month.<ref name=guide>{{cite web|title=Monmouth Town Guide|url=http://www.visitwyevalley.com/download/downloads/id/67/monmouth_town_guide_20112012|publisher=Monmouth Town Council|accessdate=10 December 2011}}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Monmouth church is part of the Newport and Lower Wye Circuit that includes other Methodist churches at [[Trellech]], [[Broadoak, Gloucestershire|Broadoak]], [[Llancloudy]] and [[Wonastow|Gwern-y-Saint]].<ref name=mess>{{cite journal|title=The Messenger|date=Oct\u2013Nov 2011|url=http://www.monmouthmethodist.org.uk/Messenger/MessengerOctNov11.pdf}}</ref><ref>[http://www.monmouthmethodist.org.uk/Messenger/MessengerOctNov11.pdf]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Buildings in Monmouth}}\n\n[[Category:Methodist churches in Wales]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Monmouth, Wales]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed churches in Monmouthshire]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical architecture in Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Will Duffield", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eThe church today)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monmouth_Methodist_Church"}
{"title_page": "Pelagianism", "text_new": "{{redirect|Pelagians|the Italian movement of lay mystics known as Pelagians|Pelagians (Quietism)}}\n'''Pelagianism''' is a [[heterodox]] [[Christian theology|Christian theological]] position which holds that the [[original sin]] did not taint [[human nature]] and that mortal [[will (philosophy)|will]] is capable of choosing [[Goodness and value theory|good]] or [[evil]] without [[Grace (Christianity)#Augustine versus Pelagius|divine aid]] or assistance. This theological theory is named after the British monk [[Pelagius]] ({{circa|355}}&nbsp;\u2013 {{circa|420}} CE), although he denied, at least at some point in his life, many of the doctrines associated with his name. Pelagianism asserts human will, as created with its abilities by God, is sufficient to live a sinless life, although God's grace assists every good work. It has come to be identified with the view (whether taught by Pelagius or not) that human beings can earn salvation by their own efforts.\n\n==Pelagian controversy==\n[[File:Nuremberg chronicles f 135r 2.jpg|thumb|right|Pelagius Hereticus and [[John Chrysostom]] depicted in the ''[[Nuremberg Chronicle]]'', 1493]]\n\n[[Pelagius]] ({{circa|355}}\u2013{{circa|420}} CE){{sfn|Elliott|2011|p=377}} was a monk, probably from the [[British Isles]], who moved to [[Rome]] in the mid-380s.{{sfn|Keech|2012|p=38}} At the time, many Romans were converting to Christianity, but they did not necessarily follow the faith strictly.{{sfn|Kirwan|1998}} Pelagius criticized what he saw as an increasing laxity among Christians, instead promoting higher moral standards and [[Christian asceticism]].{{sfn|Elliott|2011|p=377}}{{sfn|Wetzel|2001|p=51}} He defended asceticism from the accusation of [[Manicheanism]] and argued for the possibility of a [[sinless |sinless life]]. The rejection of [[original sin]] was not original to Pelagius, initially promoted by [[Rufinus the Syrian]].{{sfn|Bonner|2004}} Pelagius and his ideas were most popular among circles of the Roman elite, who adopted [[lay asceticism]] as a way of life.{{sfn|Keech|2012|p=38}}{{sfn|Wetzel|2001|p=51}} Other prominent Pelagians included the former Roman aristocrat [[Caelestius]], described by [[Gerald Bonner]] as \"the real apostle of the so-called Pelagian movement\", and the apologist [[Julian of Eclanum]].{{sfn|Bonner|2004}} According to scholar [[Ali Bonner]], the ideas Pelagius actually promoted were not a \"new heresy\", as Augustine claimed, but mainstream in contemporary Christianity, advocated by such figures as [[Athanasius of Alexandria]] and [[Jerome]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bonner |first1=Ali |title=In praise of Pelagius |url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2018/31-august/features/features/in-praise-of-pelagius |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=[[The Church Times]] |date=31 August 2018}}</ref> \n\nAugustine maintained friendly relations with Pelagius until at least 413, initially only condemning Caelestius' teachings.{{sfn|Bonner|2004}} In 415, the Gallic bishops [[Heros of Arles]] and [[Lazarus of Aix]] accused Pelagius of heresy; Pelagius defended himself by claiming not to teach what he was accused of and by ascribing some of the teachings to Caelestinus and disavowing them, leading to his acquittal at the Council of Diospolis in [[Lod]]. Following the verdict, Augustine led condemnation of Pelagius in Africa and persuaded Pope [[Innocent I]] to condemn Pelagianism. In January 417, shortly before his death, Innocent [[excommunicated]] Pelagius and two of his followers. Innocent's successor, [[Pope Zosimus|Zosimus]], initially agreed to reopen the case against Pelagius, but backtracked following pressure from the African bishops.{{sfn|Bonner|2004}}{{sfn|Keech|2012|pp=39\u201340}}  Pelagianism was later condemned at the [[Council of Carthage (418)]],{{sfn|Reese|1996|p=421}} after which Zosimus issued the ''Epistola tractoria'' excommunicating both Pelagius and Caelestinus.{{sfn|Bonner|2004}} The condemnation of Pelagianism was ratified at the [[First Council of Ephesus|Council of Ephesus]].{{sfn|Keech|2012|p=40}}\n\nAt the time, Pelagius' teachings had considerable support among Christians, especially other monks.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}} The strict moral teachings of the Pelagians were influential in southern Italy, where they were openly preached until the death of Julian of Eclanum in 455; in Sicily, where the anonymous \"[[Sicilian Briton]]\" wrote.<ref name=\"Knowles\" />{{better source|date=April 2020}} Despite repeated attempts to suppress Pelagianism and similar teachings by [[Orthodoxy|orthodox]] clergy, some followers were still active in the [[Ostrogothic Kingdom]] (493\u2013553), most notably in [[Picenum]] and [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] during the rule of [[Theoderic the Great]].{{sfn|Cohen|2016|p=523}} Pelagianism was also reported to be popular in Britain, as [[Germanus of Auxerre]] had to make at least one visit (in 429) to denounce the heresy. Some scholars, including [[Nowell Myres]] and [[John Morris (historian) |John Morris]], have suggested that Pelagianism in Britain was understood as an attack on Roman decadence and corruption, but this has been criticized by others such as [[Wolf Liebeschuetz]].{{sfn|Bonner|2004}}\n\n==Beliefs==\n\nPelagius taught that humans were free of the burden of [[original sin]], because it would be unjust for any person to be blamed for another's actions.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}} He believed that Adam's transgression had caused humans to become mortal, and given them a bad example, but not corrupted their nature.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=49}}{{efn|Caelestinus went even further, arguing that Adam had been created mortal.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=50}}}} Because humans retained [[libertarian free will|complete freedom of action]], making them fully responsible for all actions.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}  In other words, sin is not an inevitable result of [[human nature]], but instead comes about by [[free choice]].{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}} Because a person always has the ability to choose the right action in each circumstance, it is therefore theoretically possible (though rare) to live a sinless life.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}{{sfn|Kirwan|1998|loc=Pelagius}} Pelagius taught that a human's ability to act correctly is a gift of God,{{sfn|Kirwan|1998|loc=Pelagius}} as well as [[divine revelation]] and the example and teachings of Jesus. Further spiritual development, including faith in Christianity, was up to individual choice, not divine benevolence.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=48}} Because sin must be deliberate and people are only responsible for their own actions, infants are without fault and [[infant baptism]] is unnecessary.{{sfn|Kirwan|1998|loc=Grace and free will}} \nThere is significant doubt as to what Pelagius actually taught,{{cn|date=April 2020}} and what Augustine called \"Pelagianism\" was more his own invention than that of Pelagius.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=50}}{{sfn|Bonner|2018|p=302}} Later Christians used \"Pelagianism\" as an insult for theologically orthodox Christians who held positions that they disagreed with. Historian [[Eric Nelson (historian)|Eric Nelson]] defined genuine Pelagianism as rejection of original sin or denial of original sin's effect on man's ability to avoid sin.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=4}}\n===Comparison of Pelagianism and Augustinianism===\nPelagius' teachings on human nature, divine grace, and sin were opposed to those of Augustine, who declared Pelagius \"the enemy of the grace of God\".{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}} The Pelagians charged Augustine with departing from the accepted teaching (e.g.: [[John 8:11]]) of the Apostles and the Bible, demonstrating the doctrine of original sin amounted to [[Manichaeism]], which taught that the flesh was in itself sinful (and thus denied Jesus [[Incarnation (Christianity)|came in the flesh]]). This charge would have carried added weight since contemporaries knew Augustine had himself been a Manichaean layman before converting to Christianity.{{sfn|Stump|Kretzmann|2001|pp= 130\u2013135}} Pelagianism shaped Augustine's ideas in opposition to its own on free will, grace, and original sin.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=43}}{{sfn|Keech|2012|p=15}} However, according to [[Peter Brown (historian)|Peter Brown]], \"For a sensitive man of the fifth century, Manichaeism, Pelagianism, and the views of Augustine were not as widely separated as we would now see them: they would have appeared to him as points along the great circle of problems raised by the Christian religion\".{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=53}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Belief !! Pelagianism !! Augustianism\n|-\n|[[Original sin]] || Does not affect human nature{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}} ||Affects all humans since the [[Fall of man|Fall]]{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}}\n|-\n|[[Free will]] || [[Libertarian free will]]{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}} || Original sin renders men unable to choose good{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|pp=123\u2013124}}\n|-\n|Status of infants||Blameless{{sfn|Kirwan|1998|loc=Grace and free will}} ||Corrupted by original sin{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=124}}{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}}\n|-\n|[[Sin in Christianity|Sin]]|| Comes about by free choice{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}}||Inevitable result of fallen [[human nature]]{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}}\n|-\n|Forgiveness for sin || Given to those who sincerely repent and merit it{{efn|Pelagius wrote: \"pardon is given to those who repent, not according to the grace and mercy of God, but according to their own merit and effort, who through repentance will have been worthy of mercy\".{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=49}}}}|| Part of God's grace, disbursed according to his will\n|-\n|Sinless life||Theoretically possible, although unusual{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=48}}||Impossible due to the corruption of human nature{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=124}}\n|-\n|[[Salvation in Christianity|Salvation]]||Humans will be judged for their choices alone{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}||Salvation is bestowed by God's grace, although man may reject it{{sfn|Stump|Kretzmann|2001|pp= 130\u2013135}}\n|- \n|[[Predestination]]||Rejected||All events are decreed by God\n|}\nAccording to Nelson, Pelagianism is a solution to the [[problem of evil]] that invokes [[libertarian free will]] as both the cause of human suffering and a sufficient good to justify it.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=3}} By positing that man could choose between good and evil without divine intercession, Pelagianism brought into question Christianity's core doctrine of [[Jesus]]' act of [[substitutionary atonement]] to expiate the sins of mankind.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=3, 51}} Augustine argued that if man \"could have become just by the law of nature and free will . . . amounts to rendering the cross of Christ void\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=3}} For this reason, Pelagianism became associated with [[nontrinitarian]] interpretations of Christianity which rejected the [[divinity of Jesus]],{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=51}} as well as other heresies such as [[Arianism]], [[Socinianism]], and [[mortalism]] (which rejected the [[hell in Christianity|existence of hell]]).{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=4}} Augustine's solution, while it was faithful to orthodox Christology, worsened the problem of evil because according to Augustinian interpretations, God punishes sinners who by their very nature are unable not to sin. The Augustinian defense of God's grace against accusations of arbitrariness is that God's ways are incomprehensible to mere mortals.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=4}} Yet, as later critics such as [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz]] asserted, asking \"[[Euthyphro dilemma|it is good and just because God wills it or whether God wills it because it is good and just]]?\", this defense (although accepted by many Catholic and [[Reformed]] theologians) creates a [[Divine command theory|God-centered morality]], which, in Leibniz' view \"would destroy the justice of God\" and make him into a tyrant.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=5\u20136}}\n\n===Pelagianism and Judaism===\nOne of the most important distinctions between Christianity and [[Judaism]] is that the former conventionally teaches justice by faith, while the latter teaches that man has the choice to follow divine law. By teaching the absense of original sin and the idea that humans can choose between good and evil, Pelagianism advocated a position close to that of  Judaism.{{sfn|Fu|2015|p=182}} Pelagius wrote positively of Jews and Judaism, recommending that Christians study Old Testament law\u2014a sympathy not commonly encountered in Christianity after [[Paul the Apostle |Paul]].{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=48}} Augustine was the first to accuse Pelagianism of \"[[Judaizing]]\",{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=45}} which became a commonly heard criticism of it.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=51}}{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=45}} However, although contemporary rabbinic literature tends to take a Pelagian perspective on the major questions, and it could be argued that the rabbis shared a ''[[Weltanschauung]]'' with Pelagius, there were minority opinions within Judaism which argued for ideas more similar to Augustine's.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=59}} Overall, Jewish discourse did not discuss free will and emphasized God's goodness in his revelation of the [[Torah]].{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=60}}\n\n==Later responses==\n[[Thomas Bradwardine]] (c. 1290\u20131349) wrote ''De causa Dei contra Pelagium et de virtute causarum ad suos Mertonenses'' condemning Pelagianism, as did [[Gabriel Biel]] in the 15th century.{{sfn|Reese|1996|p=421}} Johann Pupper, also known as [[Johannes von Goch]] (c. 1400\u20131475), an [[Augustinian]], recommended a return to the text of the Bible as a remedy for Pelagianism.{{sfn|Webster|1980|p=783|loc=Johannes von Goch}}\n\n===Early modern era===\nPelagianism became a common accusation during the [[Protestant Reformation]]; Reformers often used the epithet to critique what they saw as late-medieval Catholicism's undue emphasis on doing [[Justification (theology)|good works]]. [[Martin Luther]] (1483\u20131546), [[John Calvin]] (1509\u20131564), and [[Cornelius Jansen]] (1585\u20131638) reacted in different ways against Pelagianism, and evaluations of [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]], [[Calvinism|Reformed]], and [[Jansenism|Jansenist]] theologies have often turned on the question of what is or is not Pelagian.{{sfn|Cottret|Cottret| Michel|2002}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nDuring the modern era, Pelagianism continued to be used as an epithet against orthodox Christians, but there were nevertheless some who had essentially Pelagian views according to Nelson's definition.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=4}} Nelson argued that many of those considered the predecessors to modern [[liberalism]] took Pelagian or Pelagian-adjanect positions on the problem of evil.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=5}} For instance, Leibniz who coined the word [[theodicy]] in 1710, rejected Pelagianism but nevertheless proved to be \"a crucial conduit for Pelagian ideas\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=2, 5}} He argued that \"Freedom is deemed necessary in order that man may be deemed guilty and open to punishment.\"{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=8}} In ''[[De doctrina christiana (Milton)|De doctrina christiana]]'', [[John Milton]] argued that \"if, because of God\u2019s decree, man could not help but fall . . . then God\u2019s restoration of fallen man was a matter of justice not grace\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=7}} Milton also argued for other positions that could be considered Pelagian, such as that \"The knowledge and survey of vice, is in this world . . . necessary to the constituting of human virtue.\"{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=11}} [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]] made nearly identical arguments for that point.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=11}} [[John Locke]] argued that the idea  that \"all ''Adam''\u2019s Posterity [are] doomed to Eternal Infinite Punishment, for the Transgression of ''Adam''\" was \"little consistent with the Justice or Goodness of the Great and Infinite God\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=7\u20138}} He did not accept that original sin corrupted human nature, and argued that man could live a Christian life (although not \"void of slips and falls\") and be entitled to justification.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=8}}\n\nNelson argues that the drive for rational justification of religion, rather than a symptom of [[secularization]], was actually \"a Pelagian response to the theodicy problem\" because \"the conviction that everything\nnecessary for salvation must be accessible to human reason was yet another inference from God\u2019s justice\". In Pelagianism, libertarian free will is [[necessary but not sufficient]] for God's punishment of humans to be justified, because man must also understand God's commands.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=15}} As a result, thinkers such as Locke, Rousseau and [[Immanuel Kant]] argued that following [[natural law]] without [[revealed religion]] must be sufficient for the salvation of those who were never exposed to Christianity because, as Locke pointed out, access to revelation is a matter of [[moral luck]].{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=16\u201318}} Early modern proto-liberals such as Milton, Locke, Leibniz, and Rousseau advocated [[religious toleration]] and freedom of private action (eventually codified as [[human rights]]), as only freely chosen actions could merit salvation.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=19\u201320}}{{efn|This is the opposite of the Augustinian argument against excessive state power, which is that human corruption is such that man cannot be trusted to wield it without creating tyranny, what [[Judith Shklar]] called \"liberalism of fear\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=21}}}}\n\nNineteenth-century philosopher [[S\u00f8ren Kierkegaard]] dealt with the same problems (nature, grace, freedom, and sin) as Augustine and Pelagius,{{sfn|Puchniak |2008|p=124}} which he believed were opposites in a [[Hegelian dialectic]].{{sfn|Puchniak |2008|p=126}} He rarely mentioned Pelagius explicitly{{sfn|Puchniak |2008|p=124}} even though he inclined towards a Pelagian viewpoint. However, Kierkegaard rejected the idea that man could perfect himself.{{sfn|Puchniak |2008|p=128}}\n\n===Contemporary responses===\nIn the book ''Guardare Cristo: Esercizi di fede, speranza e carit\u00e0'' (Looking at Christ: Exercises of faith, hope and charity),{{sfn|Ratzinger|1989|p=}} [[Pope Benedict XVI]] wrote: {{quote|the other face of the same vice is the Pelagianism of the pious. They do not want forgiveness and in general they do not want any real gift from God either. They just want to be in order. They don\u2019t want hope they just want security. Their aim is to gain the right to salvation through a strict practice of religious exercises, through prayers and action. What they lack is humility which is essential in order to love; the humility to receive gifts not just because we deserve it or because of how we act&nbsp;...|source={{harvnb|Tornielli|2013}} }}\n\nIn a June 2013 talk with the leadership of the Religious Confederation of Latin America and the Caribbean (CLAR), [[Pope Francis]] alluded to Pelagian tendencies when he referred to \"restorationists\", one group of whom sent him after his election 3,525 rosaries. The pope said he was \"bothered\" by this need to count prayers and labeled it \"pelagianism.\" He went on to comment: \"these groups return to practices and disciplines I lived \u2013 not you, none of you are old \u2013 to things that were lived in that moment, but not now, they aren't today&nbsp;...\"<ref name=\"Winters2013\" /> The [[Congregation of the Doctrine of the Faith]] subsequently emphasised \"neo-Pelagianism\" in a letter of February 2018 titled ''Placuit Deo'', stating, \"A new form of Pelagianism is spreading in our days, one in which the individual, understood to be radically autonomous, presumes to save oneself, without recognizing that, at the deepest level of being, he or she derives from God and from others.\"<ref name=\"PlacuitDeo\" />\n\n[[John Rawls]] was a critic of Pelagianism, an attitude that he retained even after becoming an athiest. His anti-Pelagian ideas influenced his book ''[[A Theory of Justice]]'', in which he argued that differences in productivity between humans are a result of \"moral arbitrariness\" and therefore unequal wealth is undeserved.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=50, 53}} According to Nelson, many contemporary [[social liberals]] follow Rawls rather than the older liberal-Pelagian tradition.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=49}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|20em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Knowles\">{{Cite web |title=Unitarian Universalists |last=Knowles |first=George |work=controverscial.com |date= |access-date=3 December 2019 |url= http://www.controverscial.com/Unitarian%20Universalists.htm |language= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Winters2013\">{{Cite web |title=Pope Francis on Pelagians, Gnostics and the CDF |last=Winters |first=Michael Sean |work=National Catholic Reporter |date=12 June 2013 |access-date=3 December 2019 |url= https://www.ncronline.org/blogs/distinctly-catholic/pope-francis-pelagians-gnostics-and-cdf |quote=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PlacuitDeo\">{{Cite web |title=Letter ''Placuit Deo'' to the Bishops of the Catholic Church on Certain Aspects of Christian Salvation |last1=Ladaria |first1=Luis F. |last2=Morandi |first2=Giacomo |work=vatican.va |date=22 February 2018 |access-date=3 December 2019 |url= https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/congregations/cfaith/documents/rc_con_cfaith_doc_20180222_placuit-deo_en.html  }}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|2|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bonner |first1=Ali |title=[[The Myth of Pelagianism]] |date=2018 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-726639-7 |language=English|series= \t[[British Academy Monograph]]}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia |first=Gerald |last = Bonner|authorlink=Gerald Bonner| publisher = Oxford University Press | encyclopedia= Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| title= Pelagius (fl. c.390\u2013418), theologian| year = 2004 | | doi= 10.1093/ref:odnb/21784 }}\n*{{cite book|last=Cohen|first=Samuel |chapter=Religious Diversity|editor1=Jonathan J. Arnold|editor2=M. Shane Bjornlie|editor3=Kristina Sessa\n|ref=harv |title=A Companion to Ostrogothic Italy|chapter-url= |date=2016|publisher= [[Brill Publishers]]|location= [[Leiden]], [[Boston]]|isbn=978-9004-31376-7|pages=503\u2013532}}\n*{{cite book|editor1-first=Bernard |editor1-last=Cottret|editor2-first= Monique |editor2-last=Cottret|editor3-first= Marie-Jos\u00e9 |editor3-last=Michel|date=2002|title=Jans\u00e9nisme et puritanisme: Actes du colloque du 15 septembre 2001, tenu au Mus\u00e9e National des Granges des Port-Royal-des-Champs|location= Paris|publisher=  Nolin|ref=harv|lang=fr|trans-title=Jansenism and puritanism: Proceedings of the colloquium of 15 September 2001 at the National Museum of Granges des Port-Royal-des-Champs|id={{HathiTrust Catalog|004289432|Jans\u00e9nisme et puritanisme}} }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Elliott |first1=Mark W. |authorlink1=Mark W. Elliott |editor1-last=McFarland |editor1-first=Ian A. |editor2-last=Fergusson |editor2-first=David A. S. |editor3-last=Kilby |editor3-first=Karen |editor4-last=Torrance |editor4-first=Iain R. |title=The Cambridge Dictionary of Christian Theology |date=2011 |isbn=978-0-511-78128-5 |pages=377\u2013378 |language=en |chapter=Pelagianism}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Fu |first1=Youde |title=The Value of the Particular: Lessons from Judaism and the Modern Jewish Experience |date=2015 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-29269-7 |pages=171\u2013194 |language=en |chapter=Hebrew Justice: A Reconstruction for Today}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|last=Kirwan|first= Christopher  |title=Pelagianism |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]]|encyclopedia=[[Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy]] |language=en|doi=10.4324/9780415249126-K064-1 |date=1998}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Nelson |first1=Eric|authorlink=Eric M. Nelson |title=The Theology of Liberalism: Political Philosophy and the Justice of God |date=2019 |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-674-24094-0 |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/arts-letters/articles/john-rawls-justice-jewish-heresy |language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Puchniak |first1=Robert |editor1-last=Stewart |editor1-first=Jon Bartley |editor1-link=Jon Stewart (philosopher) |title=Kierkegaard and the Patristic and Medieval Traditions |date=2008 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |isbn=978-0-7546-6391-1 |language=en |chapter=Pelagius: Kierkegaard's use of Pelagius and Pelagianism}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Ratzinger|first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Ratzinger|title=Guardare Cristo: esercisi di fede, speranza e carit\u00e0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mT_dfm57blsC|year=1989|publisher=Editoriale Jaca |isbn=978-88-16-30178-8|lang=it|trans-title=Looking at Christ: Exercises of faith, hope and charity}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Reese|first=William L. |title=Dictionary of Philosophy and Religion: Eastern and Western Thought|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W9TZAAAAMAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Humanity Books|isbn=978-1-57392-621-8}}\n*{{cite book|isbn=978-1-1391-7804-4|title=The Cambridge Companion to Augustine|date= 2001|editor1-first= Eleonore |editor1-last=Stump|editor2-first= Norman |editor2-last=Kretzmann|location= New York|publisher= Cambridge University Press|pp=124\u2013147|last=Stump|first=Eleonore|chapter=Augustine on free will}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://vaticaninsider.lastampa.it/en/the-vatican/detail/articolo/francesco-francis-francisco-benedetto-xvi-benedict-xvi-benedicto-xvi-25586/ |last=Tornielli|first= Andrea|title=Francis, Ratzinger and the Pelagianism risk|work=Vatican Insider/La Stampa|date= June 12, 2013|ref=harv|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213085440/http://www.lastampa.it/2013/06/12/vaticaninsider/eng/the-vatican/francis-ratzinger-and-the-pelagianism-risk-7Om60Hh0PDOal92Z1ZGFIP/pagina.html|archive-date=2017-02-13}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Visotzky |first1=Burton L. |editor1-last=Grypeou |editor1-first=Emmanouela |editor2-last=Spurling |editor2-first=Helen |title=The Exegetical Encounter Between Jews and Christians in Late Antiquity |date=2009 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-17727-7 |pages=43\u201362 |language=en |chapter=Will and Grace: Aspects of Judaising in Pelagianism in Light of Rabbinic and Patristic Exegesis of Genesis}}\n*{{cite book|isbn=978-1-1391-7804-4|title=The Cambridge Companion to Augustine|date= 2001|editor1-first= Eleonore |editor1-last=Stump|editor2-first= Norman |editor2-last=Kretzmann|location= New York|publisher= Cambridge University Press|ref=harv|chapter-url=https://www.academia.edu/859842/Predestination_Pelagianism_and_foreknowledge|last=Wetzel|first=James|chapter=Predestination, Pelagianism, and foreknowledge|pp=49\u201358}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Cyr |first1=Taylor W. |last2=Flummer |first2=Matthew T. |title=Free will, grace, and anti-Pelagianism |journal=International Journal for Philosophy of Religion |date=2018 |volume=83 |issue=2 |pages=183\u2013199 |doi=10.1007/s11153-017-9627-0 |language=en |issn=1572-8684}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Harrison |first1=Carol |title=Truth in a Heresy? |journal=The Expository Times |date=20 November 2016 |volume=112 |issue=3 |pages=78\u201382 |doi=10.1177/001452460011200302}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Keech |first1=Dominic |title=The Anti-Pelagian Christology of Augustine of Hippo, 396-430 |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-966223-4 |language=en}}\n*{{cite journal|url=http://eprints.gla.ac.uk/3310/1/Gilmarcus.pdf|last=Marcus|first=Gilbert|title=Pelagianism and the 'Common Celtic Church'|date=2005|journal=Innes Review|volume=56|issue=2|pp= 165-213}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Rackett |first1=Michael R. |title=What\u2019s Wrong with Pelagianism? |journal=Augustinian Studies |date=2002 |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=223\u2013237 |doi=10.5840/augstudies200233216}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Rees |first1=Brinley Roderick |title=Pelagius: Life and Letters |date=1998 |publisher=[[Boydell & Brewer]] Ltd |location=Woodbridge |isbn=978-0-85115-714-6 |language=en}}\n*{{cite thesis |last1=Squires |first1=Stuart|editor=[[Philip Rousseau]]|degree=PhD|institution=Catholic University of America |title=Reassessing Pelagianism: Augustine, Cassian, and Jerome on the Possibility of a Sinless Life. |date=2013 |url=https://www.academia.edu/17580213/_Reassessing_Pelagianism_Augustine_Cassian_and_Jerome_on_the_Possibility_of_a_Sinless_Life._ |language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Squires |first1=Stuart |title=The Pelagian Controversy: An Introduction to the Enemies of Grace and the Conspiracy of Lost Souls |date=2019 |publisher=[[Wipf and Stock]] |location=Eugene |isbn=978-1-5326-3781-0 |language=en}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.pelagius.net Pelagius Library]: Online site dedicated to the study of Pelagius\n\n{{Heresies condemned by the Catholic Church}}\n{{History of Catholic theology}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n[[Category:Christian theological movements]]\n[[Category:Heresy in ancient Christianity]]\n[[Category:Pelagianism]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Pelagians|the Italian movement of lay mystics known as Pelagians|Pelagians (Quietism)}}\n'''Pelagianism''' is a [[heterodox]] [[Christian theology|Christian theological]] position which holds that the [[original sin]] did not taint [[human nature]] and that mortal [[will (philosophy)|will]] is capable of choosing [[Goodness and value theory|good]] or [[evil]] without [[Grace (Christianity)#Augustine versus Pelagius|divine aid]] or assistance. This theological theory is named after the British monk [[Pelagius]] ({{circa|355}}&nbsp;\u2013 {{circa|420}} CE), although he denied, at least at some point in his life, many of the doctrines associated with his name. Pelagianism asserts human will, as created with its abilities by God, is sufficient to live a sinless life, although God's grace assists every good work. It has come to be identified with the view (whether taught by Pelagius or not) that human beings can earn salvation by their own efforts.\n\n==Pelagian controversy==\n[[File:Nuremberg chronicles f 135r 2.jpg|thumb|right|Pelagius Hereticus and [[John Chrysostom]] depicted in the ''[[Nuremberg Chronicle]]'', 1493]]\n\n[[Pelagius]] ({{circa|355}}\u2013{{circa|420}} CE){{sfn|Elliott|2011|p=377}} was a monk, probably from the [[British Isles]], who moved to [[Rome]] in the mid-380s.{{sfn|Keech|2012|p=38}} At the time, many Romans were converting to Christianity, but they did not necessarily follow the faith strictly.{{sfn|Kirwan|1998}} Pelagius criticized what he saw as an increasing laxity among Christians, instead promoting higher moral standards and [[Christian asceticism]].{{sfn|Elliott|2011|p=377}}{{sfn|Wetzel|2001|p=51}} He defended asceticism from the accusation of [[Manicheanism]] and argued for the possibility of a [[sinless |sinless life]]. The rejection of [[original sin]] was not original to Pelagius, initially promoted by [[Rufinus the Syrian]].{{sfn|Bonner|2004}} Pelagius and his ideas were most popular among circles of the Roman elite, who adopted [[lay asceticism]] as a way of life.{{sfn|Keech|2012|p=38}}{{sfn|Wetzel|2001|p=51}} Other prominent Pelagians included the former Roman aristocrat [[Caelestius]], described by [[Gerald Bonner]] as \"the real apostle of the so-called Pelagian movement\", and the apologist [[Julian of Eclanum]].{{sfn|Bonner|2004}} According to scholar [[Ali Bonner]], the ideas Pelagius actually promoted were not a \"new heresy\", as Augustine claimed, but mainstream in contemporary Christianity, advocated by such figures as [[Athanasius of Alexandria]] and [[Jerome]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bonner |first1=Ali |title=In praise of Pelagius |url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2018/31-august/features/features/in-praise-of-pelagius |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=[[The Church Times]] |date=31 August 2018}}</ref> \n\nAugustine maintained friendly relations with Pelagius until at least 413, initially only condemning Caelestius' teachings.{{sfn|Bonner|2004}} In 415, the Gallic bishops [[Heros of Arles]] and [[Lazarus of Aix]] accused Pelagius of heresy; Pelagius defended himself by claiming not to teach what he was accused of and by ascribing some of the teachings to Caelestinus and disavowing them, leading to his acquittal at the Council of Diospolis in [[Lod]]. Following the verdict, Augustine led condemnation of Pelagius in Africa and persuaded Pope [[Innocent I]] to condemn Pelagianism. In January 417, shortly before his death, Innocent [[excommunicated]] Pelagius and two of his followers. Innocent's successor, [[Pope Zosimus|Zosimus]], initially agreed to reopen the case against Pelagius, but backtracked following pressure from the African bishops.{{sfn|Bonner|2004}}{{sfn|Keech|2012|pp=39\u201340}}  Pelagianism was later condemned at the [[Council of Carthage (418)]],{{sfn|Reese|1996|p=421}} after which Zosimus issued the ''Epistola tractoria'' excommunicating both Pelagius and Caelestinus.{{sfn|Bonner|2004}} The condemnation of Pelagianism was ratified at the [[First Council of Ephesus|Council of Ephesus]].{{sfn|Keech|2012|p=40}}\n\nAt the time, Pelagius' teachings had considerable support among Christians, especially other monks.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}} The strict moral teachings of the Pelagians were influential in southern Italy, where they were openly preached until the death of Julian of Eclanum in 455; in Sicily, where the anonymous \"[[Sicilian Briton]]\" wrote.<ref name=\"Knowles\" />{{better source|date=April 2020}} Despite repeated attempts to suppress Pelagianism and similar teachings by [[Orthodoxy|orthodox]] clergy, some followers were still active in the [[Ostrogothic Kingdom]] (493\u2013553), most notably in [[Picenum]] and [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] during the rule of [[Theoderic the Great]].{{sfn|Cohen|2016|p=523}} Pelagianism was also reported to be popular in Britain, as [[Germanus of Auxerre]] had to make at least one visit (in 429) to denounce the heresy. Some scholars, including [[Nowell Myres]] and [[John Morris (historian) |John Morris]], have suggested that Pelagianism in Britain was understood as an attack on Roman decadence and corruption, but this has been criticized by others such as [[Wolf Liebeschuetz]].{{sfn|Bonner|2004}}\n\n==Beliefs==\n\nPelagius taught that humans were free of the burden of [[original sin]], because it would be unjust for any person to be blamed for another's actions.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}} He believed that Adam's transgression had caused humans to become mortal, and given them a bad example, but not corrupted their nature.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=49}}{{efn|Caelestinus went even further, arguing that Adam had been created mortal.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=50}}}} Because humans retained [[libertarian free will|complete freedom of action]], making them fully responsible for all actions.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}  In other words, sin is not an inevitable result of [[human nature]], but instead comes about by [[free choice]].{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}} Because a person always has the ability to choose the right action in each circumstance, it is therefore theoretically possible (though rare) to live a sinless life.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}{{sfn|Kirwan|1998|loc=Pelagius}} Pelagius taught that a human's ability to act correctly is a gift of God,{{sfn|Kirwan|1998|loc=Pelagius}} as well as [[divine revelation]] and the example and teachings of Jesus. Further spiritual development, including faith in Christianity, was up to individual choice, not divine benevolence.{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=48}} Because sin must be deliberate and people are only responsible for their own actions, infants are without fault and [[infant baptism]] is unnecessary.{{sfn|Kirwan|1998|loc=Grace and free will}} \nThere is significant doubt as to what Pelagius actually taught,{{cn|date=April 2020}} and what Augustine called \"Pelagianism\" was more his own invention than that of Pelagius.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=50}}{{sfn|Bonner|2018|p=302}} Later Christians used \"Pelagianism\" as an insult for theologically orthodox Christians who held positions that they disagreed with. Historian [[Eric Nelson (historian)|Eric Nelson]] defined genuine Pelagianism as rejection of original sin or denial of original sin's effect on man's ability to avoid sin.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=4}}\n===Comparison of Pelagianism and Augustinianism===\nPelagius' teachings on human nature, divine grace, and sin were opposed to those of Augustine, who declared Pelagius \"the enemy of the grace of God\".{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}} The Pelagians charged Augustine with departing from the accepted teaching (e.g.: [[John 8:11]]) of the Apostles and the Bible, demonstrating the doctrine of original sin amounted to [[Manichaeism]], which taught that the flesh was in itself sinful (and thus denied Jesus [[Incarnation (Christianity)|came in the flesh]]). This charge would have carried added weight since contemporaries knew Augustine had himself been a Manichaean layman before converting to Christianity.{{sfn|Stump|Kretzmann|2001|pp= 130\u2013135}} Pelagianism shaped Augustine's ideas in opposition to its own on free will, grace, and original sin.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=43}}{{sfn|Keech|2012|p=15}} However, according to [[Peter Brown (historian)|Peter Brown]], \"For a sensitive man of the fifth century, Manichaeism, Pelagianism, and the views of Augustine were not as widely separated as we would now see them: they would have appeared to him as points along the great circle of problems raised by the Christian religion\".{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=53}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Belief !! Pelagianism !! Augustianism\n|-\n|[[Original sin]] || Does not affect human nature{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}} ||Affects all humans since the [[Fall of man|Fall]]{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}}\n|-\n|[[Free will]] || [[Libertarian free will]]{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}} || Original sin renders men unable to choose good{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|pp=123\u2013124}}\n|-\n|Status of infants||Blameless{{sfn|Kirwan|1998|loc=Grace and free will}} ||Corrupted by original sin{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=124}}{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}}\n|-\n|[[Sin in Christianity|Sin]]|| Comes about by free choice{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}}||Inevitable result of fallen [[human nature]]{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=44}}\n|-\n|Forgiveness for sin || Given to those who sincerely repent and merit it{{efn|Pelagius wrote: \"pardon is given to those who repent, not according to the grace and mercy of God, but according to their own merit and effort, who through repentance will have been worthy of mercy\".{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=49}}}}|| Part of God's grace, disbursed according to his will\n|-\n|Sinless life||Theoretically possible, although unusual{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=48}}||Impossible due to the corruption of human nature{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=124}}\n|-\n|[[Salvation in Christianity|Salvation]]||Humans will be judged for their choices alone{{sfn|Puchniak|2008|p=123}}||Salvation is bestowed by God's grace, although man may reject it{{sfn|Stump|Kretzmann|2001|pp= 130\u2013135}}\n|- \n|[[Predestination]]||Rejected||All events are decreed by God\n|}\nAccording to Nelson, Pelagianism is a solution to the [[problem of evil]] that invokes [[libertarian free will]] as both the cause of human suffering and a sufficient good to justify it.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=3}} By positing that man could choose between good and evil without divine intercession, Pelagianism brought into question Christianity's core doctrine of [[Jesus]]' act of [[substitutionary atonement]] to expiate the sins of mankind.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=3, 51}} Augustine argued that if man \"could have become just by the law of nature and free will . . . amounts to rendering the cross of Christ void\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=3}} For this reason, Pelagianism became associated with [[nontrinitarian]] interpretations of Christianity which rejected the [[divinity of Jesus]],{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=51}} as well as other heresies such as [[Arianism]], [[Socinianism]], and [[mortalism]] (which rejected the [[hell in Christianity|existence of hell]]).{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=4}} Augustine's solution, while it was faithful to orthodox Christology, worsened the problem of evil because according to Augustinian interpretations, God punishes sinners who by their very nature are unable not to sin. The Augustinian defense of God's grace against accusations of arbitrariness is that God's ways are incomprehensible to mere mortals.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=4}} Yet, as later critics such as [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz]] asserted, asking \"[[Euthyphro dilemma|it is good and just because God wills it or whether God wills it because it is good and just]]?\", this defense (although accepted by many Catholic and [[Reformed]] theologians) creates a [[Divine command theory|God-centered morality]], which, in Leibniz' view \"would destroy the justice of God\" and make him into a tyrant.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=5\u20136}}\n\n===Pelagianism and Judaism===\nOne of the most important distinctions between Christianity and [[Judaism]] is that the former conventionally teaches justice by faith, while the latter teaches that man has the choice to follow divine law. By teaching the absense of original sin and the idea that humans can choose between good and evil, Pelagianism advocated a position close to that of  Judaism.{{sfn|Fu|2015|p=182}} Pelagius wrote positively of Jews and Judaism, recommending that Christians study Old Testament law\u2014a sympathy not commonly encountered in Christianity after [[Paul the Apostle |Paul]].{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=48}} Augustine was the first to accuse Pelagianism of \"[[Judaizing]]\",{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=45}} which became a commonly heard criticism of it.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=51}}{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=45}} However, although contemporary rabbinic literature tends to take a Pelagian perspective on the major questions, and it could be argued that the rabbis shared a ''[[Weltanschauung]]'' with Pelagius, there were minority opinions within Judaism which argued for ideas more similar to Augustine's.{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=59}} Overall, Jewish discourse did not discuss free will and emphasized God's goodness in his revelation of the [[Torah]].{{sfn|Visotzky|2009|p=60}}\n\n==Later responses==\n[[Thomas Bradwardine]] (c. 1290\u20131349) wrote ''De causa Dei contra Pelagium et de virtute causarum ad suos Mertonenses'' condemning Pelagianism, as did [[Gabriel Biel]] in the 15th century.{{sfn|Reese|1996|p=421}} Johann Pupper, also known as [[Johannes von Goch]] (c. 1400\u20131475), an [[Augustinian]], recommended a return to the text of the Bible as a remedy for Pelagianism.{{sfn|Webster|1980|p=783|loc=Johannes von Goch}}\n\n===Early modern era===\nPelagianism became a common accusation during the [[Protestant Reformation]]; Reformers often used the epithet to critique what they saw as late-medieval Catholicism's undue emphasis on doing [[Justification (theology)|good works]]. [[Martin Luther]] (1483\u20131546), [[John Calvin]] (1509\u20131564), and [[Cornelius Jansen]] (1585\u20131638) reacted in different ways against Pelagianism, and evaluations of [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]], [[Calvinism|Reformed]], and [[Jansenism|Jansenist]] theologies have often turned on the question of what is or is not Pelagian.{{sfn|Cottret|Cottret| Michel|2002}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nDuring the modern era, Pelagianism continued to be used as an epithet against orthodox Christians, but there were nevertheless some who had essentially Pelagian views according to Nelson's definition.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=4}} Nelson argued that many of those considered the predecessors to modern [[liberalism]] took Pelagian or Pelagian-adjanect positions on the problem of evil.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=5}} For instance, Leibniz who coined the word [[theodicy]] in 1710, rejected Pelagianism but nevertheless proved to be \"a crucial conduit for Pelagian ideas\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=2, 5}} He argued that \"Freedom is deemed necessary in order that man may be deemed guilty and open to punishment.\"{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=8}} In ''[[De doctrina christiana (Milton)|De doctrina christiana]]'', [[John Milton]] argued that \"if, because of God\u2019s decree, man could not help but fall . . . then God\u2019s restoration of fallen man was a matter of justice not grace\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=7}} Milton also argued for other positions that could be considered Pelagian, such as that \"The knowledge and survey of vice, is in this world . . . necessary to the constituting of human virtue.\"{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=11}} [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]] made nearly identical arguments for that point.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=11}} [[John Locke]] argued that the idea  that \"all ''Adam''\u2019s Posterity [are] doomed to Eternal Infinite Punishment, for the Transgression of ''Adam''\" was \"little consistent with the Justice or Goodness of the Great and Infinite God\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=7\u20138}} He did not accept that original sin corrupted human nature, and argued that man could live a Christian life (although not \"void of slips and falls\") and be entitled to justification.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=8}}\n\nNelson argues that the drive for rational justification of religion, rather than a symptom of [[secularization]], was actually \"a Pelagian response to the theodicy problem\" because \"the conviction that everything\nnecessary for salvation must be accessible to human reason was yet another inference from God\u2019s justice\". In Pelagianism, libertarian free will is [[necessary but not sufficient]] for God's punishment of humans to be justified, because man must also understand God's commands.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=15}} As a result, thinkers such as Locke, Rousseau and [[Immanuel Kant]] argued that following [[natural law]] without [[revealed religion]] must be sufficient for the salvation of those who were never exposed to Christianity because, as Locke pointed out, access to revelation is a matter of [[moral luck]].{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=16\u201318}} Early modern proto-liberals such as Milton, Locke, Leibniz, and Rousseau advocated [[religious toleration]] and freedom of private action (eventually codified as [[human rights]]), as only freely chosen actions could merit salvation.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=19\u201320}}{{efn|This is the opposite of the Augustinian argument against excessive state power, which is that human corruption is such that man cannot be trusted to wield it without creating tyranny, what [[Judith Shklar]] called \"liberalism of fear\".{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=21}}}}\n\nNineteenth-century philosopher [[S\u00f8ren Kierkegaard]] dealt with the same problems (nature, grace, freedom, and sin) as Augustine and Pelagius,{{sfn|Puchniak |2008|p=124}} which he believed were opposites in a [[Hegelian dialectic]].{{sfn|Puchniak |2008|p=126}} He rarely mentioned Pelagius explicitly{{sfn|Puchniak |2008|p=124}} even though he inclined towards a Pelagian viewpoint. However, Kierkegaard rejected the idea that man could perfect himself.{{sfn|Puchniak |2008|p=128}}\n\n===Contemporary responses===\nIn the book ''Guardare Cristo: Esercizi di fede, speranza e carit\u00e0'' (Looking at Christ: Exercises of faith, hope and charity),{{sfn|Ratzinger|1989|p=}} [[Pope Benedict XVI]] wrote: {{quote|the other face of the same vice is the Pelagianism of the pious. They do not want forgiveness and in general they do not want any real gift from God either. They just want to be in order. They don\u2019t want hope they just want security. Their aim is to gain the right to salvation through a strict practice of religious exercises, through prayers and action. What they lack is humility which is essential in order to love; the humility to receive gifts not just because we deserve it or because of how we act&nbsp;...|source={{harvnb|Tornielli|2013}} }}\n\nIn a June 2013 talk with the leadership of the Religious Confederation of Latin America and the Caribbean (CLAR), [[Pope Francis]] alluded to Pelagian tendencies when he referred to \"restorationists\", one group of whom sent him after his election 3,525 rosaries. The pope said he was \"bothered\" by this need to count prayers and labeled it \"pelagianism.\" He went on to comment: \"these groups return to practices and disciplines I lived \u2013 not you, none of you are old \u2013 to things that were lived in that moment, but not now, they aren't today&nbsp;...\"<ref name=\"Winters2013\" /> The [[Congregation of the Doctrine of the Faith]] subsequently emphasised \"neo-Pelagianism\" in a letter of February 2018 titled ''Placuit Deo'', stating, \"A new form of Pelagianism is spreading in our days, one in which the individual, understood to be radically autonomous, presumes to save oneself, without recognizing that, at the deepest level of being, he or she derives from God and from others.\"<ref name=\"PlacuitDeo\" />\n\n[[John Rawls]] was a critic of Pelagianism, an attitude that he retained even after becoming an athiest. His anti-Pelagian ideas influenced his book ''[[A Theory of Justice]]'', in which he argued that differences in productivity between humans are a result of \"moral arbitrariness\" and therefore unequal wealth is undeserved.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|pp=50, 53}} According to Nelson, many contemporary [[social liberals]] follow Rawls rather than the older liberal-Pelagian tradition.{{sfn|Nelson|2019|p=49}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|20em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Knowles\">{{Cite web |title=Unitarian Universalists |last=Knowles |first=George |work=controverscial.com |date= |access-date=3 December 2019 |url= http://www.controverscial.com/Unitarian%20Universalists.htm |language= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Winters2013\">{{Cite web |title=Pope Francis on Pelagians, Gnostics and the CDF |last=Winters |first=Michael Sean |work=National Catholic Reporter |date=12 June 2013 |access-date=3 December 2019 |url= https://www.ncronline.org/blogs/distinctly-catholic/pope-francis-pelagians-gnostics-and-cdf |quote=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PlacuitDeo\">{{Cite web |title=Letter ''Placuit Deo'' to the Bishops of the Catholic Church on Certain Aspects of Christian Salvation |last1=Ladaria |first1=Luis F. |last2=Morandi |first2=Giacomo |work=vatican.va |date=22 February 2018 |access-date=3 December 2019 |url= https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/congregations/cfaith/documents/rc_con_cfaith_doc_20180222_placuit-deo_en.html  }}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|2|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bonner |first1=Ali |title=[[The Myth of Pelagianism]] |date=2018 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-726639-7 |language=English|series= \t[[British Academy Monograph]]}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia |first=Gerald |last = Bonner|authorlink=Gerald Bonner| publisher = Oxford University Press | encyclopedia= Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| title= Pelagius (fl. c.390\u2013418), theologian| year = 2004 | | doi= 10.1093/ref:odnb/21784 }}\n*{{cite book|last=Cohen|first=Samuel |chapter=Religious Diversity|editor1=Jonathan J. Arnold|editor2=M. Shane Bjornlie|editor3=Kristina Sessa\n|ref=harv |title=A Companion to Ostrogothic Italy|chapter-url= |date=2016|publisher= [[Brill Publishers]]|location= [[Leiden]], [[Boston]]|isbn=978-9004-31376-7|pages=503\u2013532}}\n*{{cite book|editor1-first=Bernard |editor1-last=Cottret|editor2-first= Monique |editor2-last=Cottret|editor3-first= Marie-Jos\u00e9 |editor3-last=Michel|date=2002|title=Jans\u00e9nisme et puritanisme: Actes du colloque du 15 septembre 2001, tenu au Mus\u00e9e National des Granges des Port-Royal-des-Champs|location= Paris|publisher=  Nolin|ref=harv|lang=fr|trans-title=Jansenism and puritanism: Proceedings of the colloquium of 15 September 2001 at the National Museum of Granges des Port-Royal-des-Champs|id={{HathiTrust Catalog|004289432|Jans\u00e9nisme et puritanisme}} }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Elliott |first1=Mark W. |authorlink1=Mark W. Elliott |editor1-last=McFarland |editor1-first=Ian A. |editor2-last=Fergusson |editor2-first=David A. S. |editor3-last=Kilby |editor3-first=Karen |editor4-last=Torrance |editor4-first=Iain R. |title=The Cambridge Dictionary of Christian Theology |date=2011 |isbn=978-0-511-78128-5 |pages=377\u2013378 |language=en |chapter=Pelagianism}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Fu |first1=Youde |title=The Value of the Particular: Lessons from Judaism and the Modern Jewish Experience |date=2015 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-29269-7 |pages=171\u2013194 |language=en |chapter=Hebrew Justice: A Reconstruction for Today}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|last=Kirwan|first= Christopher  |title=Pelagianism |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]]|encyclopedia=[[Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy]] |language=en|doi=10.4324/9780415249126-K064-1 |date=1998}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Nelson |first1=Eric|authorlink=Eric M. Nelson |title=The Theology of Liberalism: Political Philosophy and the Justice of God |date=2019 |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-674-24094-0 |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/arts-letters/articles/john-rawls-justice-jewish-heresy |language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Puchniak |first1=Robert |editor1-last=Stewart |editor1-first=Jon Bartley |editor1-link=Jon Stewart (philosopher) |title=Kierkegaard and the Patristic and Medieval Traditions |date=2008 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |isbn=978-0-7546-6391-1 |language=en |chapter=Pelagius: Kierkegaard's use of Pelagius and Pelagianism}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Ratzinger|first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Ratzinger|title=Guardare Cristo: esercisi di fede, speranza e carit\u00e0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mT_dfm57blsC|year=1989|publisher=Editoriale Jaca |isbn=978-88-16-30178-8|lang=it|trans-title=Looking at Christ: Exercises of faith, hope and charity}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Reese|first=William L. |title=Dictionary of Philosophy and Religion: Eastern and Western Thought|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W9TZAAAAMAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Humanity Books|isbn=978-1-57392-621-8}}\n*{{cite book|isbn=978-1-1391-7804-4|title=The Cambridge Companion to Augustine|date= 2001|editor1-first= Eleonore |editor1-last=Stump|editor2-first= Norman |editor2-last=Kretzmann|location= New York|publisher= Cambridge University Press|pp=124\u2013147|last=Stump|first=Eleonore|chapter=Augustine on free will}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://vaticaninsider.lastampa.it/en/the-vatican/detail/articolo/francesco-francis-francisco-benedetto-xvi-benedict-xvi-benedicto-xvi-25586/ |last=Tornielli|first= Andrea|title=Francis, Ratzinger and the Pelagianism risk|work=Vatican Insider/La Stampa|date= June 12, 2013|ref=harv|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213085440/http://www.lastampa.it/2013/06/12/vaticaninsider/eng/the-vatican/francis-ratzinger-and-the-pelagianism-risk-7Om60Hh0PDOal92Z1ZGFIP/pagina.html|archive-date=2017-02-13}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Visotzky |first1=Burton L. |editor1-last=Grypeou |editor1-first=Emmanouela |editor2-last=Spurling |editor2-first=Helen |title=The Exegetical Encounter Between Jews and Christians in Late Antiquity |date=2009 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-17727-7 |pages=43\u201362 |language=en |chapter=Will and Grace: Aspects of Judaising in Pelagianism in Light of Rabbinic and Patristic Exegesis of Genesis}}\n*{{cite book|isbn=978-1-1391-7804-4|title=The Cambridge Companion to Augustine|date= 2001|editor1-first= Eleonore |editor1-last=Stump|editor2-first= Norman |editor2-last=Kretzmann|location= New York|publisher= Cambridge University Press|ref=harv|url=https://www.academia.edu/859842/Predestination_Pelagianism_and_foreknowledge|last=Wetzel|first=James|chapter=Predestination, Pelagianism, and foreknowledge|pp=49\u201358}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Cyr |first1=Taylor W. |last2=Flummer |first2=Matthew T. |title=Free will, grace, and anti-Pelagianism |journal=International Journal for Philosophy of Religion |date=2018 |volume=83 |issue=2 |pages=183\u2013199 |doi=10.1007/s11153-017-9627-0 |language=en |issn=1572-8684}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Harrison |first1=Carol |title=Truth in a Heresy? |journal=The Expository Times |date=20 November 2016 |volume=112 |issue=3 |pages=78\u201382 |doi=10.1177/001452460011200302}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Keech |first1=Dominic |title=The Anti-Pelagian Christology of Augustine of Hippo, 396-430 |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-966223-4 |language=en}}\n*{{cite journal|url=http://eprints.gla.ac.uk/3310/1/Gilmarcus.pdf|last=Marcus|first=Gilbert|title=Pelagianism and the 'Common Celtic Church'|date=2005|journal=Innes Review|volume=56|issue=2|pp= 165-213}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Rackett |first1=Michael R. |title=What\u2019s Wrong with Pelagianism? |journal=Augustinian Studies |date=2002 |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=223\u2013237 |doi=10.5840/augstudies200233216}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Rees |first1=Brinley Roderick |title=Pelagius: Life and Letters |date=1998 |publisher=[[Boydell & Brewer]] Ltd |location=Woodbridge |isbn=978-0-85115-714-6 |language=en}}\n*{{cite thesis |last1=Squires |first1=Stuart|editor=[[Philip Rousseau]]|degree=PhD|institution=Catholic University of America |title=Reassessing Pelagianism: Augustine, Cassian, and Jerome on the Possibility of a Sinless Life. |date=2013 |url=https://www.academia.edu/17580213/_Reassessing_Pelagianism_Augustine_Cassian_and_Jerome_on_the_Possibility_of_a_Sinless_Life._ |language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Squires |first1=Stuart |title=The Pelagian Controversy: An Introduction to the Enemies of Grace and the Conspiracy of Lost Souls |date=2019 |publisher=[[Wipf and Stock]] |location=Eugene |isbn=978-1-5326-3781-0 |language=en}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.pelagius.net Pelagius Library]: Online site dedicated to the study of Pelagius\n\n{{Heresies condemned by the Catholic Church}}\n{{History of Catholic theology}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n[[Category:Christian theological movements]]\n[[Category:Heresy in ancient Christianity]]\n[[Category:Pelagianism]]\n", "name_user": "Buidhe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pelagianism"}
{"title_page": "Tony Bellew", "text_new": "{{short description|British boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Tony Bellew\n| image =\n| caption = Bellew in 2016\n| realname = Anthony Lewis Bellew\n| nickname = Bomber\n| weight = {{plainlist|\n*[[Light-heavyweight]]\n*[[Cruiserweight (boxing)|Cruiserweight]]\n*[[Heavyweight]]\n}}greatest line for god sake man you\u2019ve got a hair band on\n\n| height = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=stats2018>[[Sky Box Office]] tale of the tape prior to the second [[David Haye]] fight.</ref>\n| reach = 74 in<ref name=stats2018/>\n| nationality = British\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|11|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toxteth]], [[Liverpool]], England\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 34\n| wins = 30\n| KO = 20\n| losses = 3\n| draws = 1\n}}\n\n'''Anthony Lewis Bellew''' (born 30 November 1982)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxing247.com/weblog/archives/137444 |date=30 March 2012 |title=Tony Bellew slams Clev's opponent selection |website=East Side Boxing}}</ref> is a British former [[professional boxer]] who competed from 2007 to 2018. He held the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[cruiserweight (boxing)|cruiserweight]] title from 2016 to 2017, and challenged for the [[undisputed champion|undisputed]] cruiserweight championship in his final fight. At regional level, Bellew held the [[British Boxing Board of Control|British]] and [[Commonwealth Boxing Council|Commonwealth]] [[light-heavyweight]] titles between 2010 and 2014, the [[European Boxing Union|European]] cruiserweight title from 2015 to 2016, and is a three-time [[England Boxing|ABA]] [[heavyweight]] champion as an [[amateur boxing|amateur]].<ref name=\"Liverpool Echo Bellew vs Ajisafe\"/> Outside of boxing, he was featured in the 2015 film ''[[Creed (film)|Creed]]''.\n\n==Amateur career==\nFighting out of [[Liverpool]]'s Rotunda ABC, Bellew claimed both the 2002 and 2003 novice [[Amateur Boxing Association of England|ABA]] titles by knocking out every man he faced with the exception of Rob Hough who went the 3 rounds from Paramount ABC (Stockport) in the under 10 bouts championships.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}} Then, when he was eligible for the Senior championships, he stepped up to the 91&nbsp;kg heavyweight class and added even more titles to his collection. In 2006 he lost to [[Danny Price (boxer)|Danny Price]].{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}\n\n==Professional career==\n\n=== Light-heavyweight ===\n\n==== Early career ====\nBellew made his professional boxing debut on 6 October 2007 against journeyman Jamie Ambler and made a winning start with a second-round win. He followed up the victory with further wins in 2007 over Adam Wilcox, fighting at the [[Millennium Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]] and Wayne Brooks at the [[Bolton Arena]].<ref name=\"Boxrec Tony Bellew\">{{Cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=425328&cat=boxer|title=BoxRec - Tony Bellew|website=boxrec.com|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Bellew defeated Paul Bonson, Ayitey Powers, Hastings Rasani, Jevg\u0113\u0146ijs Andrejevs, and Phil Goodwin to take his record up to 8\u20130. During 2009 he advanced to an unbeaten 12\u20130 with further wins against Matthew Ellis, Nick Okoth, Jindrich Velecky, and Martial Bella Oleme.<ref name=\"Boxrec Tony Bellew\" />\n\n====Commonwealth champion====\nOn 12 March 2010 Bellew challenged for the vacant [[List of Commonwealth Boxing Council champions#Light heavyweight|Commonwealth light-heavyweight title]], defeating Atoli Moore at the [[Echo Arena]] in Liverpool.<ref>[http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/boxing/2010/03/13/champion-paul-smith-survives-cut-to-triumph-in-bloody-battle-against-tony-dodson-at-liverpool-echo-arena-100252-26023264/ Liverpool Echo | Smith vs Dodson with undercard report of Bellew vs Moore]</ref> He made his first defence of the title on 24 September 2010, defeating [[Bob Ajisafe]] at the [[Grosvenor House Hotel]] in London with Bellew having to recover from a flash knockdown during the fight.<ref name=\"Liverpool Echo Bellew vs Ajisafe\">[http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/boxing/2010/09/25/tony-bellew-taken-championship-distance-as-he-defends-commonwealth-light-heavyweight-belt-against-bob-ajisafe-100252-27339367/ Liverpool Echo | Tony Bellew taken championship distance as he defends Commonwealth light-heavyweight belt against Bob Ajisafe ]</ref> He made his second defence of the title on 9 December 2010, returning to the Echo Arena to stop former Commonwealth champion [[Ovill McKenzie]] in the eighth-round despite suffering two knockdowns himself in both the first and second rounds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/boxing/2010/12/13/tony-bellew-shows-power-to-defeat-ovill-mckenzie-100252-27814619/|title=Tony Bellew shows power to defeat Ovill MCKenzie|last=Echo|first=Liverpool|date=13 December 2010|work=liverpoolecho|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May 2011 it was announced that Bellew would challenge [[Nathan Cleverly]] for the [[List of WBO world champions#Light heavyweight|WBO light-heavyweight title]] following a pullout from Cleverly's scheduled opponent [[J\u00fcrgen Br\u00e4hmer]] with the fight due to be held only three days later on 21 May 2011. Bellew however, failed to make the weight and was replaced with [[Aleksy Kuziemski]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/13460425|title=Nathan Cleverly records first world title defence|last=SPORT|first=Nabil Hassan BBC|website=BBC Sport|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref> On 16 July 2011 Bellew made the third defence of his Commonwealth title and also won the vacant [[List of British light-heavyweight boxing champions|British title]] with a repeat victory over Ovill McKenzie, with the bout this time lasting the full twelve rounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/9485042.stm|title=BBC Sport - Tony Bellew aiming to beat Ovill McKenzie in style|website=news.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2011/7/16/2279132/bellew-vs-mckenzie-results-frankie-gavin-vs-woodhouse-uk-boxing-news|title=Tony Bellew Wins Dull Decision Over Ovill McKenzie, Frankie Gavin Disappoints Again|last=Christ|first=Scott|date=16 July 2011|website=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Bellew vs. Cleverly ====\nIt was announced that Bellew would fight Nathan Cleverly in Liverpool, on 15 October 2011, for the WBO light-heavyweight title. Cleverly won the fight via [[majority decision]] (MD). One judge scored the bout at 114\u2013114 whereas the other two judges scored the bout at 116\u2013113, and 117\u2013112.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/15315836|title=Nathan Cleverly beats Bellew to retain WBO light-heavyweight belt|date=15 October 2011|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2 March 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/oct/16/nathan-cleverly-tony-bellew-boxing|title=Nathan Cleverly wins one for Wales as he retains WBO title|last=Arena|first=Jamie Jackson at the Liverpool Echo|date=15 October 2011|work=The Guardian|access-date=2 March 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing to Cleverly, Bellew took on [[Danny McIntosh]] for the vacant British light-heavyweight title, knocking McIntosh out in the fifth round. Next he took on former world title challenger [[Edison Miranda]] for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] International title, and stopped Miranda in the ninth round.\n\n==== Bellew vs. Chilemba I, II ====\nOn 17 November 2012 he beat [[Roberto Bolonti]] for the [[WBC Silver]] title. Bellew was cut badly but went the full twelve rounds to a win [[unanimous decision]] (UD), taking him one step further to a second world title fight. On 30 March 2013, he fought [[Isaac Chilemba]] in a title eliminator. The judges scored it a controversial draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/8609057/tony-bellew-fights-to-controversial-draw-with-isaac-chilemba-at-echo-arena|title=Tony Bellew fights to controversial draw with Isaac Chilemba at Echo Arena|last=|first=|date=5 May 2013|website=Sky Sports|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/9963524/Tony-Bellew-held-to-a-draw-by-Isaac-Chilemba-in-WBC-light-heavyweight-fight.html|title=Tony Bellew held to a draw by Isaac Chilemba in WBC light-heavyweight fight|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> Chilemba granted a rematch which Bellew won on the scorecards after twelve rounds via UD, with 117\u2013112, and 116\u2013112 twice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/22668071|title=Tony Bellew beats Isaac Chilemba to become mandatory challenger|date=25 May 2013|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2 March 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2013/5/25/4365946/bellew-vs-chilemba-ii-results-tony-bellew-wins-competitive-decision|title=Results: Bellew tops Chilemba in rematch|last=Christ|first=Scott|date=25 May 2013|website=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Bellew vs. Stevenson ====\n\nBellew was made [[mandatory challenger]] for the [[List of WBC world champions#Light heavyweight|WBC light-heavyweight title]] following the win against Chilemba. However, a fight between [[Adonis Stevenson]] and [[Tavoris Cloud]] occurred on 28 September 2013 with the winner being made to defend his title against Bellew before the end of the year. Stevenson became the first boxer to stop Bellew, winning the fight via [[technical knockout]] (TKO). In round six, Stevenson put Bellew down with a left hand, he beat the count and the referee let the fight go on. Bellew was then on the receiving end of another pair of left hands before the referee could get in and put a stop to the bout. At the time of stoppage, Stevenson was ahead on the scorecards with  50\u201345 twice, and 49\u201346.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/boxing/article-2516331/Tony-Bellew-loses-world-title-fight-Adonis-Stevenson-wants-Carl-Froch.html|title='Superman' Stevenson stops brave Brit Bellew in sixth round to retain world title before calling out Froch and Hopkins|last=|first=|date=1 December 2013|website=|publisher=|access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9051880/wbc-light-heavyweight-champion-adonis-stevenson-became-first-to-stop-tony-bellew|title=WBC light-heavyweight champion Adonis Stevenson became first to stop Tony Bellew|last=|first=|date=1 December 2013|website=[[Sky Sports]]|publisher=|access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/25173669|title=Tony Bellew beaten by Adonis Stevenson in WBC title fight|last=|first=|date=1 December 2013|website=|publisher=|access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref> Bellew contemplated moving up to [[Cruiserweight (boxing)|cruiserweight]] after the loss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/25219334|title=Tony Bellew: Adonis Stevenson defeat prompts cruiserweight move|last=|first=|date=5 December 2013|website=BBC Boxing|publisher=|access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref> According to [[Nielsen Media Research]] firm, the fight attracted an average of 1.3&nbsp;million viewers on the [[HBO]] network, making it the fifth most watched bout of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/nielsen-ratings-1-3-million-tune-into-stevensonkovalev-twinbill-on-hbo-during-thanksgiving-weekend-232498|title=Nielsen Ratings: 1.3 million tune into Stevenson/Kovalev twinbill on HBO during Thanksgiving Weekend.|accessdate=5 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Cruiserweight ===\nBellew celebrated his first fight as a cruiserweight with a twelfth-round [[knockout]] (KO) of [[Valery Brudov]] on 15 March 2014 at the Echo Arena in Liverpool. This was for the vacant WBO International cruiserweight title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/bout/1859007|title=BoxRec \u2013 Tony Bellew v Valery Brudov|website=boxrec.com|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref> Bellew successfully defended the title on 12 July 2014 against Julio Cesar Dos Santos via fifth-round TKO. Dos Santos went down following a left to the jaw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/bout/1898258|title=BoxRec \u2013 Tony Bellew v Julio Cesar Dos Santos|website=boxrec.com|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Bellew vs. Cleverly II ====\nOn 22 November 2014 Bellew got his rematch against Nathan Cleverly, this time fighting as cruiserweights. The fight took place at the Echo Arena in Liverpool also a [[List of WBO world champions#Junior heavyweight|WBO cruiserweight championship]] eliminator. The title was held by [[Marco Huck]] at the time. The bout went twelve rounds as Bellew won via [[split decision]] (SD). One judge scored the bout 115\u2013114 in favour of Cleverly whereas the other two judges scored the bout 116\u2013112, and 115\u2013113 in favour of Bellew. In the post-fight interview, Bellew said, \"I'm over the moon, listen it's over, it's put to bed. We said a lot of things. I don't like him now, but it's been settled tonight. It's over, it's done and I've outworked a great athlete.\" He also stated that he would accept a rematch at Millennium Stadium if there was any demand for it. Cleverly said he struggled with dealing with Bellew at a higher weight. After the fight, Cleverly moved back down to light-heavyweight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/31680/9576081/cleverly-v-bellew-ii-tony-bellew-triumphs-in-rematch-with-points-win-over-nathan-cleverly|title=Cleverly v Bellew II: Tony Bellew triumphs in rematch with points win over Nathan Cleverly|work=Sky Sports|access-date=14 June 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/30165714|title=Tony Bellew beats Nathan Cleverly after 12 rounds in Liverpool|date=23 November 2014|work=BBC Sport|access-date=14 June 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bellew fought two lower ranked opponents, defeating Ivica Ba\u010durin via tenth-round TKO and Art\u016brs Ku\u013cikauskis via fifth-round TKO.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/boxing/result/result-tony-bellew-eases-to-win-over-bacurin_230551.html|title=Result: Tony Bellew eases to win over Bacurin|work=Sports Mole|access-date=2 March 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2015/09/tony-bellew-vs-arturs-kulikauskis-this-saturday-in-leeds/|title=Tony Bellew vs. Arturs Kulikauskis this Saturday in Leeds \" Boxing News|date=3 September 2015|work=Boxing News 24|access-date=2 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxing247.com/boxing-news/tony-bellewarturs-kulikauskis-mis-match-added-to-underwhelming-night-in-leeds/45826|title=Tony Bellew/Arturs Kulikauskis Mis-Match Added to Underwhelming Night in Leeds - Boxing News|date=3 September 2015|access-date=2 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/9980790/tony-bellew-remains-on-track-for-world-title-shot-after-stoppage-win|title=Tony Bellew remains on track for world title shot after stoppage win|last=|first=|date=6 September 2015|website=Sky Sports|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Bellew vs. Masternak ====\nOn 29 November 2015, [[Sky Sports]] confirmed that Bellew would fight highly ranked contender and former world title challenger [[Mateusz Masternak]] (36\u20133, 26 KOs) for the vacant [[List of European Boxing Union champions#Cruiserweight|European cruiserweight title]]. The fight took place on 12 December at the O2 Arena in London, as part of the undercard for [[Anthony Joshua vs. Dillian Whyte]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10061124/tony-bellew-will-fight-mateusz-masternak-at-the-o2-on-december-12|title=Tony Bellew will fight Mateusz Masternak at the O2 on December 12|last=|first=|date=29 November 2015|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=8 August 2016}}</ref> Bellew produced a solid performance as the fight with Masternak was back and forth throughout. Going into the twelfth round, Bellew was winning by one round. Bellew won the fight via UD, with scores of 115\u2013113, and 115\u2013112 twice to capture the European title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x3rjyn0|title=Tony Bellew vs Mateusz Masternak - 12-12-2015 by Boxingfights HD - Dailymotion|date=11 February 2016|website=Dailymotion|language=en-US|access-date=30 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/boxing/tony-bellew-claims-european-title-10591265|title=Tony Bellew claims European title with points victory over Mateusz Masternak|last=McKenna|first=Micheal|date=12 December 2015|work=liverpoolecho|access-date=30 October 2017}}</ref> Bellew earned an \u00a380,000 purse for the bout.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/boxing/tony-bellew-vs-oleksandr-usyk-fight-how-much-winner-make-net-worth-prize-money-time-watch-video-a8627791.html|title=How much money will Bellew and Usyk make from cruiserweight fight?|work=The Independent|access-date=2019-04-15|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====Bellew vs. Makabu====\nOn 29 May 2016, Bellew challenged for the [[List of WBC world champions#Cruiserweight|WBC cruiserweight title]], vacated by [[Grigory Drozd]], who had been injured and not fought since his KO win in May 2015. Bellew faced [[Ilunga Makabu]] (19\u20131, 18 KOs), who had not lost since his debut back in 2008, at [[Goodison Park]] in Liverpool. Makabu was scheduled to fight Drozd, only for the Russian to pull out with an injury, prompting the WBC to strip him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2016/04/tony-bellew-vs-ilunga-makabu-529-goodison-park/|title=Tony Bellew vs. Ilunga Makabu on 5/29 at Goodison Park|date=20 April 2016|website=Boxing News 24|language=en-US|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref> Bellew weighed in at 14st 3lbs 1oz while Makabu took to the scales at just over 14st.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10297304/tony-bellew-weighs-in-nearly-three-pounds-heavier-than-ilunga-makabu|title=Bellew weighs 3 lbs more than Makabu|last=|first=|date=28 May 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2016}}</ref> Bellew overcame a first-round knockdown to KO Makabu and become WBC champion, winning his first world title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10299048/tony-bellew-knocks-out-ilunga-makabu-to-win-wbc-world-cruiserweight-title-at-goodison-park|title=Bellew wins WBC Cruiserweight World title|last=|first=|date=29 May 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=30 May 2016}}</ref> During the post-fight interview, Bellew called out [[Denis Lebedev]], but not in Russia and [[David Haye]] at cruiserweight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10299118/tony-bellew-wants-to-fight-david-haye-at-cruiserweight|title=Bellew calls out Lebedev and Haye|last=|first=|date=29 May 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Bellew vs. Flores ====\nBellew announced he would be making his first voluntary defence of his world title at the Echo Arena on 15 October, against 37-year-old [[BJ Flores]] (32\u20132\u20131, 20 KOs) live on Sky Sports. This was the first time Flores challenged for a major world title, having previously fought for an [[Interim championship|interim]] title and the [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10537799/tony-bellew-to-fight-bj-flores-in-liverpool-on-october-15|title=Tony Bellew to fight BJ Flores in Liverpool on October 15|last=|first=|date=26 August 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=2 October 2016}}</ref> The WBC stated the winner had to fight [[Mairis Briedis]] next, the mandatory challenger, following his win over [[Olanrewaju Durodola]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10557944/tony-bellew-must-face-mairis-briedis-if-he-beats-bj-flores-say-wbc|title=Tony Bellew must face Mairis Briedis if he beats BJ Flores, say WBC|last=|first=|date=30 August 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=2 October 2016}}</ref> Briedis also fought on the undercard, stopping unbeaten prospect [[Simon Vallily]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10618970/bellew-vs-flores-mairis-briedis-stops-simon-vallily-to-set-up-tony-bellew-clash|title=Mairis Briedis stops Simon Vallily to set up Tony Bellew clash|last=|first=|date=15 October 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vitalboxing.com/article.asp?a=4334|title=Vital Boxing {{!}} Briedis Ready for Bellew Mandatory Defence|last=Ltd|first=Vitalnetwork|website=www.vitalboxing.com|access-date=16 October 2016|date=16 October 2016}}</ref> Briedis agreed to take a step aside fee to allow this fight to take place.\n\nAfter an even first round, the second round produced more action as Bellew hit Flores with a low blow. The referee did not see this as below the belt, however, Flores stopped for a few seconds to motion the referee that he had been hit with a low blow. Whilst doing so, Bellew piled on more pressure, eventually knocking Flores down. Bellew knocked Flores down a further two times in round two, securing a 10\u20136 round in his favour. After a fourth knockdown in round three, Flores failed to beat the referee's count, declaring Bellew the winner via KO and making a first successful defence of his WBC title. Following the win, Bellew called out former Cruiserweight and [[heavyweight]] world champion David Haye, who was ringside, repeating that he was next. Referring to Haye as '[[SpongeBob SquarePants (character)|SpongeBob]]', Bellew carried on the verbal assault in the post-fight interview using profanity and taunting Haye, stating he has been 'conning the British public' since he announced his comeback. Eddie Hearn claimed the fight could take place at heavyweight or at cruiserweight for Bellew's WBC title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/37669398|title=Tony Bellew defends WBC world cruiserweight title by stopping BJ Flores|date=15 October 2016|newspaper=BBC Sport|language=en-GB|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/boxing/tony-bellew-charges-out-of-ring-to-confront-david-haye-after-beating-bj-flores_sto5914442/story.shtml?|title=Tony Bellew charges out of ring to confront David Haye after beating BJ Flores|date=16 October 2016|newspaper=Eurosport UK|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2016/10/16/eddie-hearns-hopes-to-persuade-david-haye-into-contest-with-tony/?|title=Eddie Hearn hopes to persuade David Haye into contest with Tony Bellew|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Heavyweight ===\n\n==== Bellew vs. Haye I, II ====\nOn 25 November 2016, Eddie Hearn announced via [[Twitter]] that Bellew's next fight would be against Haye. The fight date was set for 4 March 2017 at The O2 Arena, London and was shown on [[Sky Box Office]] and was Bellew's first heavyweight fight. Due to the fight being at heavyweight, Bellew's WBC cruiserweight title was not on the line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10671658/david-haye-and-tony-bellew-will-face-each-other-in-a-huge-domestic-clash-on-sky-sports-box-office|title=David Haye and Tony Bellew will face each other in a huge domestic clash on Sky Sports Box Office|last=|first=|date=25 November 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2016/11/25/news/david-haye-v-tony-bellew-set-for-march-4-in-london-at-heavyweight?|title=David Haye v Tony Bellew set for March 4 in London at heavyweight|last=|first=|date=25 November 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the first press conference on 30 November, a fight broke out as Bellew and Haye went face to face and it appeared on the replay, Haye had managed to land a left hook on Bellew, leaving a mark. Both fighters were then separated before going their own ways.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ringtv.com/475425-david-haye-tony-bellew-press-conference-erupts/|title=DAVID HAYE-TONY BELLEW PRESS CONFERENCE ERUPTS|last=|first=|date=30 November 2016|website=The Ring|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref> On 3 March 2017, Haye weighed 224.9 lbs, heavier than Bellew who came in at 213 lbs, a career high.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ringtv.com/487289-weigh-alert-haye-224-9-bellew-213-8/|title=Weigh-in alert: Haye 224.9, Bellew 213.8 - The Ring|date=3 March 2017|work=The Ring|access-date=3 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnewsonline.net/david-haye-and-tony-bellew-weigh-in/|title=David Haye and Tony Bellew weigh in - Boxing News|date=3 March 2017|work=Boxing News|access-date=3 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The bout started as a stalemate until the sixth round, where Haye injured his ankle and fell down twice. Bellew then took control of the fight as Haye opted to continue. Bellew knocked Haye down and out of the ropes late in the eleventh round. Haye managed to make it to his feet, but his trainer [[Shane McGuigan]] threw in the towel, giving Bellew a TKO win. Bellew credited Haye for his bravery, while Haye refused to blame his injury and stated that Bellew was \"by far the better fighter\", though stated that he wanted a rematch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/39170236|title=Tony Bellew beats David Haye with 11th-round stoppage|last=Reddy|first=Luke|date=5 March 2017|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=5 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/tony-bellew-drops-stops-david-haye-massive-upset-results--114239|title=Tony Bellew Drops, Stops David Haye in MASSIVE Upset - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=6 March 2017}}</ref> Bellew contemplated retiring after claiming he had done it all. He also revealed he broke his hand in the early rounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/B/BOX_HAYE_BELLEW?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2017-03-04-18-40-02|title=News from The Associated Press|website=hosted.ap.org|access-date=6 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305003840/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/B/BOX_HAYE_BELLEW?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2017-03-04-18-40-02|archivedate=5 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the time of stoppage, Bellew lead on all three scorecards 96\u201393. With a 60\u201340 split of the \u00a37&nbsp;million purse, Haye earned \u00a34.2&nbsp;million while Bellew eaned \u00a32.8 million, his biggest purse by far.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/boxing/david-haye-pocket-14m-more-9973518|title=David Haye's purse revealed after defeat by Tony Bellew|last=Domin|first=Martin|date=6 March 2017|work=mirror|access-date=6 March 2017}}</ref> It was reported that the fight generated 890,000 buys on Sky Box Office PPV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.givemesport.com/1038905-anthony-joshua-to-receive-substantial-payday-for-wladimir-klitschko-fight|title=The staggering amount Joshua will pocket from Klitschko fight [Sun]|date=26 April 2017|website=GiveMeSport|access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, Hearn said that Bellew would fight again in 2017, a day later, he told Sky Sports that Bellew may need surgery on his broken hand which could see him out of action for up to five months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10801043/tony-bellew-will-fight-again-this-year-says-eddie-hearn|title=Tony Bellew will fight again this year, says Eddie Hearn|last=|first=|date=14 March 2017|website=Sky Sports|access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10802856/tony-bellew-may-need-hand-surgery-after-win-over-david-haye-and-faces-five-month-lay-off|title=Tony Bellew may need hand surgery after win over David Haye and faces five-month lay-off|last=|first=|date=15 March 2017|website=Sky Sports|access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, the WBC changed Bellew's world championship status to Emeritus champion. This also meant the winner between Marco Huck and Mairis Briedis on 1 April would become new world champion and not interim, as it was initially announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/briedis-huck-now-full-wbc-title-bellew-made-emeritus-champ--115057|title=Briedis-Huck Now For Full WBC Title, Bellew Made Emeritus Champ - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=29 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wbcboxing.com/wbceng/news/8335-tony-bellew-officially-appointed-emeritus-champion|title=World Boxing Council|last=Landeros|first=Jose|website=wbcboxing.com|language=en-gb|access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref> The bout was won by Briedis, thus making him the new WBC champion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/39468221|title=Mairis Briedis v Marco Huck: Tony Bellew's WBC cruiserweight title claimed by Latvian|date=1 April 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=26 April 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Bellew stated that he would next fight in either November or December 2017. He had three potential names to consider, those being [[WBC Heavyweight Champion|WBO heavyweight champion]] [[Joseph Parker (boxer)|Joseph Parker]], [[WBC Heavyweight Champion|WBC heavyweight champion]] [[Deontay Wilder]] and a rematch with Haye. Parker was his main interest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/bellew-ill-back-november-december-i-prefer-parker--117236|title=Bellew: I'll Be Back in November or December - I Prefer Parker - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Bellew admitted that a potential fight with widely regarded [[pound for pound]] number one fighter and unified light-heavyweight champion [[Andre Ward]] was of interest and the teams of the respective fighters were currently in negotiations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/21/tony-bellew-reveals-he-and-eddie-hearn-have-opened-talks-with-pound-for-pound-king-andre-ward-6724320/|title=Tony Bellew confirms he is in talks with Andre Ward for cruiserweight showdown|last=Metro.co.uk|first=Coral Barry for|date=21 June 2017|website=Metro|access-date=11 July 2017}}</ref> On 3 August, Hearn stated a rematch between Bellew and Haye was 'virtually dead', due to both fighters believing they are the A-side and have the right to demand ring walks, poster, changing rooms and split of purse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/hearn-bellew-haye-ii-virtually-dead-impossible-reach-deal--119127|title=Hearn: Bellew-Haye II is Virtually Dead, Impossible To Reach Deal - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=5 August 2017}}</ref> On 6 September, Hearn stated a deal could be made within seven days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2017/09/06/news/bellew-v-haye-ii-on-the-horizon-heading-for-december-date|title=Bellew v Haye II on the horizon, heading for December date|last=Haye|first=Bellew v|website=WBN - World Boxing News|access-date=6 September 2017|date=6 September 2017}}</ref> According to trainer David Coldwell, both Haye and Bellew had held positive talks and looking more likely to agree to a fight, as long they stay on the same page and agree to the same terms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/20615876/tony-bellew-david-haye-holding-positive-talks-rematch|title=Bellew and Haye hold 'positive talks' over rematch|work=ESPN.com|access-date=7 September 2017}}</ref> On 19 September, Haye agreed all the terms and tweeted Bellew to sign the contract. He said, \"It's taken months of negotiating but teams have finally agreed all terms for Haye-Bellew 2. Will Bellew put pen to paper?\" The fight was reported to take place on Sunday 17 December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/41318521|title=David Haye and Tony Bellew set for heavyweight rematch|date=19 September 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=20 September 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> Promoter Eddie Hearn stated the fight was not a done deal, but he had hoped to confirm the fight within a week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11043158/haye-vs-bellew-eddie-hearn-says-nothing-is-signed-yet-for-the-rematch-between-tony-bellew-and-david-haye|title=Haye vs Bellew: Eddie Hearn says nothing is signed yet for the rematch between Tony Bellew and David Haye|work=Sky Sports|access-date=20 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> Bellew replied the following day, tweeting, \"I OBLIGE YOU @mrdavidhaye , happy? Now leave me alone with my family please. I'll see you soon enough!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2017/09/20/news/tony-bellew-accepts-david-haye-rematch|title=Tony Bellew accepts David Haye rematch|last=Haye|first=Bellew v|work=WBN - World Boxing News|access-date=20 September 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref> The fight was officially confirmed on 29 September for the fight to take place at The O2 Arena in London. Bellew claimed the rematch wasn't personal any more, just business and hoping to dedicate a win to his late brother-in-law, who had died in August. Haye stated that Bellew wouldn't win the lottery twice. Like the first fight, it was scheduled to be shown live on Sky Box Office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/20857642/david-haye-vs-tony-bellew-rematch-o2-arena-december|title=Haye vs. Bellew rematch set for December|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11057767/bellew-vs-haye-ii-rematch-between-tony-bellew-and-david-haye-to-be-shown-live-on-daccess|date=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 November, it was reported that Haye had injured his arm and forced to pull out of the fight. In a statement, Haye said, \"I am devastated to announce my much-anticipated rematch against Tony Bellew has been postponed until 24 March or 5 May, subject to scheduling. It was believed that the injury occurred during a stair conditioning session. Bellew was said to be disappointed with Haye's announcement, but stated he may take an interim bout.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/42056678|title=David Haye v Tony Bellew: Rematch postponed after Haye's 'freak' accident|date=20 November 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=21 November 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/21488748/injured-david-haye-withdraws-rematch-tony-bellew|title=Injured Haye withdraws from Bellew rematch|work=ESPN.com|access-date=21 November 2017}}</ref> Hours after the cancellation was confirmed, [[Tyson Fury]] released a video on [[social media]] calling out Bellew. In the video, he said, \"I'll be ready, willing and waiting to fight Tony Bellew, May 5, O2 Arena, London.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11136081/tyson-fury-vows-to-replace-david-haye-as-tony-bellew-opponent|title=Tyson Fury vows to replace David Haye as Tony Bellew opponent|work=Sky Sports|access-date=21 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> [[Dillian Whyte]] tweeted Hearn about taking Haye's place and then called Bellew a coward for declining the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/dillian-whyte-throws-hat-ring-fight-bellew-replace-haye--122639|title=Dillian Whyte Throws Hat in Ring To Fight Bellew, Replace Haye - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=21 November 2017}}</ref> Speaking about a potential Fury fight, trainer Dave Coldwell said, \"That's not a fight I would entertain whatsoever. Fury is big, long and very, very clever in that ring. There's no way that I'd be interested in that fight.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/bellews-coach-rejects-tyson-fury-1217-no-way--122674|title=Bellew's Coach Rejects Tyson Fury For 12/17: No Way! - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref> The fight was rescheduled for 5 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11157436/tony-bellews-rematch-with-david-haye-rescheduled-at-the-o2-on-may-5-live-on-sky-sports-box-office|title=Tony Bellew's rematch with David Haye rescheduled at The O2 on May 5, live on Sky Sports Box Office|work=Sky Sports|access-date=5 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> Haye weighed 220.2 lbs, 4 lbs lighter than the first fight. Bellew also came in lighter 210.4 lbs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tony-bellew-lighter-david-haye-rematch-weigh--127821|title=Tony Bellew Lighter Than David Haye At Rematch Weigh-In|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-05-04|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nBellew knocked Haye down three times, eventually winning the fight via TKO in round five. Haye started the opening two rounds using his jab, leaving a mark around Bellew's right eye. As round three began, both boxers started getting closer and unloading power shots. As Haye started to step backwards around the ring, Bellew landed clean, dropping Haye. At this point it appeared Haye may have injured his ankle, with the Sky Sports commentary team mentioning this, as well as the post-fight interviewer. Haye later denied he was injured. Bellew then dropped Haye again with a hard combination. Bellew came out cautiously in round four, still wary of Haye's power. In round five, both traded punches, but it was a left hook from Bellew that dropped Haye a third time. Haye managed to beat the count again, not long before Bellew started unloading a barrage of punches. With Haye against the ropes, referee Howard Foster stepped in at 2 minutes 14 seconds, giving Bellew his second stoppage win over Haye.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tony-bellew-drops-david-haye-three-times-stops-him-results--127870|title=Tony Bellew Drops David Haye Three Times, Stops Him in Fifth|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-05-07|language=en-us}}</ref> Immediately after the fight Haye congratulated Bellew on the win. Bellew went on to dedicate the win to Ashley, his brother-in-law, who had died in August 2017. He also mentioned Andre Ward, who his team had brief negotiations with in 2017. Haye stated he would review the tapes and see what went wrong.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/11360806/bellew-vs-haye-2-tony-bellew-stops-david-haye-in-fifth-round-at-the-o2|title=Bellew vs Haye 2: Tony Bellew stops David Haye in fifth round at The O2|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-05-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/haye-ill-review-fight-then-decide-on-career--127894|title=Haye: I'll Have To Review The Fight, Then Decide on Career|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-05-08|language=en-us}}</ref> According to [[CompuBox]] stats, Haye landed 42 of 189 punches thrown (22%), only 6 being power punches and Bellew landed 70 of his 219 thrown (32%), with 34 being power punches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/bellew-vs-haye-rematch-compubox-punch-stats--127891|title=Bellew vs. Haye Rematch - CompuBox Punch Stats|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-05-08|language=en-us}}</ref> Both boxers earned a minimum purse of \u00a32.5 million for the fight, which would increase based on TV revenue and PPV shares.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2018/05/05/david-haye-vs-tony-bellew-prize-money-much-fight-purse-will/|title=David Haye vs Tony Bellew prize money: how much of the fight purse will the winner receive?|last=Sport|first=Telegraph|date=2018-05-05|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-05-08|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to cruiserweight ===\n\n==== Bellew vs. Usyk ====\nOn 21 July 2018, [[Oleksandr Usyk]] (15\u20130, 11 KOs) defeated [[Murat Gassiev]] via US to become the [[List of undisputed world boxing champions#Cruiserweight|undisputed cruiserweight world champion]]. When asked who he would like to fight next, Usyk said, \"At this time I have heard that Tony Bellew wants to fight the winner of the Muhammad Ali Trophy. I hope he will see me talking.... 'hey Tony Bellew, are you ready?' If he doesn't want to go down, I will go up for him. I will eat more spaghetti for my dinner!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11444932/oleksandr-usyk-beats-murat-gassiev-to-become-undisputed-cruiserweight-champion|title=Oleksandr Usyk calls out Tony Bellew after beating Murat Gassiev|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-07-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/usyk-if-bellew-come-down-ill-face-him-heavyweight--130181|title=Usyk: If Bellew Won't Come Down - I'll Face Him at Heavyweight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-24|language=en-us}}</ref> Bellew responded via social media that he would accept the fight, however stated the fight would need to take place in 2018 and for the undisputed championship. Bellew believed a fight at heavyweight would not be as appealing as he would not gain much with a win. Bellew also stated it would be his last fight as a professional.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/hearn-bellew-vs-usyk-very-early-talks-we-want-fight--130423|title=Hearn: Bellew vs. Usyk in Very Early Talks, We Want The Fight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11454479/bellew-vs-usyk-tony-bellew-says-he-will-have-to-retire-after-fighting-oleksandr-usyk|title=Bellew vs Usyk: Tony Bellew says he will have to retire after fighting Oleksandr Usyk|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en}}</ref> By the end of July, it was said the fight would likely take place in November 2018 in London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnewsonline.net/tony-bellew-eyes-november-date-for-oleksandr-usyk-showdown/|title=Tony Bellew eyes November date for Oleksandr Usyk showdown - Boxing News|date=2018-08-03|work=Boxing News|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en-US}}</ref> After positive meetings between Eddie Hearn and K2's Alexander Krassyuk, on 20 August, Boxing Scene reported the fight was likely to take place on 10 November 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11472601/eddie-hearn-hopeful-tony-bellew-oleksandr-usyk-fight-will-be-made-after-positive-meeting-in-paris|title=Eddie Hearn hopeful Tony Bellew-Oleksandr Usyk fight will be made after positive meeting in Paris|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/usyk-vs-bellew-play-november-10-london--131076|title=Usyk vs. Bellew In Play For November 10 in London|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en-us}}</ref> A week later, K2 Promotions confirmed the date of the fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/usyks-promoter-bellew-fight-on-track-november-10--131291|title=Usyk's Promoter: Bellew Fight on Track For November 10|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en-us}}</ref> On 5 September, the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] ordered Usyk to start negotiating with Denis Lebedev, who was their 'champion in recess' and gave them until the first week of October 2018 to complete negotiations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2018/9/5/17823104/wba-orders-oleksandr-usyk-to-face-denis-lebedev|title=WBA orders Oleksandr Usyk to face Denis Lebedev|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2018-09-08}}</ref> This was said to be a stumbling block for the potential Usyk vs. Bellew fight. According to Hearn, the fight was likely to be pushed back to 2019. Prior to negotiations, Bellew stated the fight must happen in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11491169/tony-bellews-fight-with-oleksandr-usyk-unlikely-for-2018-says-eddie-hearn|title=Tony Bellew's fight with Oleksandr Usyk 'unlikely for 2018', says Eddie Hearn|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-09-08|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/usyk-vs-bellew-now-rests-on-wbas-order-lebedev-fight--131532|title=Usyk vs. Bellew Now Rests on WBA's Order For Lebedev Fight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-09-08|language=en-us}}</ref> On 7 September, Usyk signed a multi-fight deal with [[Matchroom Boxing]], which meant he would fight exclusively on Sky Sports in the UK and [[DAZN]] in the US.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11490039/oleksandr-usyk-to-fight-on-sky-sports-after-signing-with-matchroom-boxing|title=Oleksandr Usyk to fight on Sky Sports after signing with Matchroom Boxing|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en}}</ref> A week after signing with Matchroom, the Usyk vs. Bellew fight was announced to take place on 10 November at the [[Manchester Arena]], live and exclusive on Sky Box Office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11497539/usyk-vs-bellew-tony-bellew-to-face-undisputed-cruiserweight-king-oleksandr-usyk-in-manchester|title=Usyk vs Bellew: Tony Bellew to face undisputed cruiserweight king Oleksandr Usyk in Manchester|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/usyk-vs-bellew-finalized-november-10-manchester-arena--131807|title=Usyk vs. Bellew Finalized - November 10 in Manchester Arena|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-us}}</ref> Experienced British referee Terry O'Connor was named as the official.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11541846/usyk-vs-bellew-terry-oconnor-to-referee-world-cruiserweight-title-fight|title=Usyk vs Bellew: Terry O'Connor to referee world cruiserweight title fight|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref> Bellew weighed 199\u00bc lbs, just over 2 years since he last made the cruiserweight limit and Usyk weighed 198\u00bc lbs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/bellew-weighs-slightly-more-usyk-cruiserweight-return--133552|title=Bellew Weighs Slightly More Than Usyk For Cruiserweight Return|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en-us}}</ref> Bellew's guaranteed purse for the fight was \u00a34 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/boxing/1043322/bellew-vs-usyk-purse-cruiserweight-fight|title=Bellew vs Usyk: Tony Bellew to pocket mammoth pay day in cruiserweight fight|last=McKenna|first=Chris|date=2018-11-10|work=Express.co.uk|access-date=2018-11-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn fight night, Usyk, who is usually a slow starter, eventually took full control of the bout and stopped Bellew in round eight to retain all the cruiserweight belts. The official time of the stoppage was at 2 minutes of round eight. There was very little action in round one as both boxers showed each other respect. Due to the lack of action, the crowd began to boo towards the end of the round. Overall, Usyk landed just three jabs and Bellew landed one power shot. Round two was similar, however Bellew stepped on the gas and landed some clean shots along with some showboating. Bellew took control in round three, landing two straight right hands. Usyk began using his jab more and after landing an overhand left, Bellew was left slightly shaken. By the end of round four, Bellew was backed up against the ropes and looked to tire. Bellew aimed most of his shots to Usyk's body and by round seven, was missing a lot of shots, mostly due to Usyk's foot movement, and ended the round with a bloodied nose. In round eight, whilst in a neutral corner, Usyk landed a hard left, again buzzing Bellew, forcing him to move away against the ropes. Another left hand wobbled Bellew before Usyk finished him off with another left which dropped Bellew backwards with his head landing on the bottom rope. A brave Bellew tried to get up slowly and beat the count but referee Terry O'Connor stopped the fight. Bellew's ten-fight winning streak came to an end. Judges Alejandro Cid and Steve Gray scored the first seven rounds 68\u201365 and 67\u201366 respectively in favour of Bellew, while Yury Koptsev had the fight 67\u201367.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/oleksandr-usyk-blasts-tony-bellew-knockout-results--133598|title=Oleksandr Usyk Blasts Tony Bellew For Knockout Win in Eight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11551101/usyk-vs-bellew-tony-bellew-falls-short-in-attempt-to-dethrone-cruiserweight-king-oleksandr-usyk|title=Usyk vs Bellew: Tony Bellew falls short in attempt to dethrone cruiserweight king Oleksandr Usyk|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfterwards, Bellew paid tribute to Usyk and announced his retirement from boxing, saying, \"I have been doing this for 20 years, and it is over.\" Usyk stated 2018 was the most difficult year of his career, but most successful. \"We need to put goals in front of us and move towards them,\" Usyk later stated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/46167379|title=Oleksandr Usyk beats Tony Bellew to remain undisputed world cruiserweight champion|date=2018-11-11|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11551110/usyk-vs-bellew-tony-bellew-labels-victorious-oleksandr-usyk-the-greatest-man-i-have-ever-shared-a-ring-with|title=Usyk vs Bellew: Tony Bellew labels victorious Oleksandr Usyk 'the greatest man I have ever shared a ring with'|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en}}</ref> There was a small concern during Bellew's post-fight interview as many felt he was clearly concussed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/av/boxing/46186822|title=Tony Bellew: Costello and Bunce debate if he should have been interviewed after Usyk defeat|date=2018-11-12|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> According to CompuBox stats, Usyk landed 112 of his 424 punches thrown (26%) and Bellew landed 61 of his 268 thrown (23%). Both landed 47 power shots each.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/oleksandr-usyk-vs-tony-bellew-compubox-punch-stats--133631|title=Oleksandr Usyk vs. Tony Bellew - CompuBox Punch Stats|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n=== Retirement ===\nBellew announced his retirement in the ring following his defeat to Usyk. He retired with a record of 30 wins from 34 professional bouts, with 20 coming inside the distance. He suffered 3 losses and one draw. All three losses came against reigning world champions. During the post-fight press conference, Bellew stated, \"It's definitely over now, you won\u2019t see me in a boxing ring again. I just want a normal life, I don\u2019t want this pressure. I only created the name Tony Bellew to make my dad proud. I\u2019ve never been Tony Bellew, I\u2019ve always been Anthony. Everyone who truly knows me calls me Anthony. Tony Bellew died on Saturday, Anthony Bellew comes back alive. I want reality back.\" He claimed his body could not longer take it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.worldboxingnews.net/2018/11/13/tony-bellew-never-return-retirement/|title=No Comebacks: Tony Bellew vows never to return following retirement|date=2018-11-13|work=WBN - World Boxing News|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tony-bellew-i-retire-my-body-t-take-it-no-more--133640|title=Tony Bellew: I Had To Retire, My Body Can't Take it No More|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-us}}</ref> On 22 November 2018, via social media, Bellew posted a video and a statement officially confirming his retirement from boxing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11560767/tony-bellew-confirms-retirement-from-boxing|title=Tony Bellew confirms retirement from boxing|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBellew is biracial; his mother is of African descent and his father is of European descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/tonybellew/status/389392534105239552 |title=Tony Bellew|publisher=Twitter}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/tonybellew/status/391489900237053952 |title=Tony Bellew|publisher=Twitter}}</ref> He first lived on Mulgrave Street, [[Toxteth]], Liverpool, but moved to Smithdown Road in Wavertree, Liverpool.<ref>{{Citation|last=Sky Sports Boxing|title=Tony Bellew on his struggles, being knocked down & Usyk tactics {{!}} Meeting John Conteh|date=2018-11-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rJ1ucW3VdCA&t=59s|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref>\n\nBellew is an avid supporter of [[Everton F.C.|Everton FC]], and has been paraded on the [[Goodison Park]] pitch at half-time during a game. He enters the ring to the theme from ''[[Z-Cars]]'', the same song that the players enter the pitch to during matches at Everton's home ground, Goodison Park.\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=1\n|ko-wins=20\n|ko-losses=2\n|dec-wins=10\n|dec-losses=1\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|34\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|30\u20133\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Oleksandr Usyk]]\n|KO\n|8 (12), {{small|2:00}} \n|10 Nov 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Manchester Arena, Manchester, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|For [[list of WBA world champions#Cruiserweight|WBA (Super)]], WBC, [[list of IBF w