{"title_page": "9th Marine Infantry Brigade", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=9th Marine Infantry Brigade\n|native_name=9{{sup|e}} Brigade d'Infanterie de Marine\n| image= 9e B.L.B.Ma.jpg\n|caption=Badge\n|dates= 1 July 1870 - ''present''\n|country=France\n|allegiance=\n|branch=[[French Army]]\n|type=[[Armour]]\n|role=[[Amphibious warfare]]\n|size= ~ 8,000 \n|command_structure=[[1st Armored Division (France)|1st Division]]\n|current_commander=\n|garrison=[[Poitiers]]\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=''Semper et Ubique'' (''[[Latin|La]]'')<br>''Toujours et Partout'' (''[[French language|Fr]]'')<br>''Always and All over'' (''[[English language|Eng]]'')\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n'''9th Colonial Infantry Division'''<br>\n[[World War II]]\n*[[Operation Dragoon]]\n[[Indochina War]]<br>\n'''9th Brigade'''<br>\n'''9th Marine Infantry Division'''<br>\n[[Lebanese Civil War]]\n*[[Multinational Force in Lebanon]]\n[[Gulf War]]<br>\n[[Bosnian War]]<br>\n'''9th Light Armoured Marine Brigade'''<br>\n'''9th Marine Infantry Brigade'''<br>\n[[Global War on Terrorism| Global War on Terrorism (2001\u2013present)]]\n|notable_commanders=\n|anniversaries=\n}}\n\nThe '''9{{sup|th}} Marine Infantry Brigade''' ({{lang-fr|9{{sup|e}} Brigade d'Infanterie de Marine, 9{{sup|e}} BIMa}}) is a light armoured, amphibious unit of the ''[[Troupes de marine]]'' of the [[French Army]].\n\nIn July 1963, the 9{{sup|e}} Brigade was created in [[Brittany]]. On 1 January 1976, the 9th Brigade became the 9th Marine Infantry Division (9{{sup|e}} division d'Infanterie de Marine, 9{{sup|e}} DIMa), attached to the land intervention force, then the [[Rapid Action Force (FAR)|Rapid Action Force]] from 1984. On 1 July 1999, the 9th Marine Infantry Division became the 9th Marine Light Armoured Brigade. On 1 January 2013, the unit was renamed and downsized to the 9th Marine Infantry Brigade ({{lang-fr|9{{sup|e}} Brigade d'Infanterie de Marine, 9{{sup|e}} BIMa}}).\n\n== Creation and different nominations ==\n\n* 1943 - 1947 : creation of the 9th Colonial Infantry Division ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:9e division d'infanterie coloniale|9e Division d'Infanterie Coloniale]], 9<sup>e</sup> D.I.C }})\n* 1963 - 1976 : designated as 9th Brigade ({{lang-fr|9<sup>e</sup> Brigade, 9<sup>e</sup>B }})\n* 1976 - 1999 : designated as 9th Marine Infantry Division ({{lang-fr|9<sup>e</sup> Division d'Infanterie de Marine, 9<sup>e</sup> D.I.Ma }})\n* 1999 - 2013 : designated as 9th Light Armoured Marine Brigade ({{lang-fr|9<sup>e</sup> Brigade L\u00e9g\u00e8re Blind\u00e9e de Marine, 9<sup>e</sup> B.L.B.Ma }})\n* 2013\u2013present : designated as '''9th Marine Infantry Brigade''' ({{lang-fr|9<sup>e</sup> Brigade d'Infanterie de Marine, 9<sup>e</sup> B.I.Ma }})\n\n== History ==\n[[File:9th Colonial Division landing Elba 16 June 1944.jpg|thumb|right|Landing French 9th Colonial Infantry Division troops during the invasion of Elba. 16 June 1944.]]\nThe division is heir to the [[Blue Division (Second French Empire)|Blue Division]] which fought during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870, in particular during the [[Battle of Bazeilles]] and the 9th Colonial Infantry Division, part of the [[Free French Forces]], which distinguished themselves in the apprehending of [[Elba]] in June 1944 and the [[Operation Dragoon|disembarking in Provence]] on 15 August of the same year. The Division then made way to [[Indochina]], where it was placed dormant (without being dissolved) in December 1947. The unit was reactivated in July 1963 in [[Brittany]] under the designation of 9th Brigade. On 1 January 1976, the division was baptized as 9th Marine Infantry Division 9<sup>e</sup> DIMa. Accordingly, the division was attached to the terrestrial intervention force, then the [[Rapid Action Force (France)|Rapid Action Force]] (FAR) since 1983. On 1 July 1999, the unit was restructured in a brigade and was designated as 9th Light Armoured Marine Brigade (BLBMa). On 1 January 2013, the brigade was named to the current designation as the '''9th Marine Infantry Brigade''' (9<sup>e</sup> BIMa).\n\nThe headquarter staff is stationed in [[Poitiers]] since 1 July 2010. The motto of the brigade is \u00ab Semper et Ulbique \u00bb, [[Latin]] for \u00ab Always and All over \u00bb.\n\nThe \u00ab 9th \u00bb illustrated capability on all exterior theatres of operations where [[France]] has been engaged since [[World War II]]: [[Indochina War|Indochina]], [[Lebanese Civil War|Lebanon]], [[Gulf War|Kuwait]], Macedonia, [[Kosovo]], [[Bosnian War|Bosnia]], [[Republic of Congo|Congo]], [[Tchad]], [[Ivory Coast]]. From October 2010 to May 2011, the Brigade armed essentially [[Brigade La Fayette]] in [[Afghanistan]] by projecting a headquarter staff ( composed 50% of Marines, Bigors, Marine sapeurs of the 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa) and the tactical interam groupment of Richelieu armed by the [[2nd Marine Infantry Regiment]] 2<sup>e</sup> RIMa. On January 2013, elements of the Brigade took part in [[Operation Serval]].\n\nIn all [[combat]] engagement theatres around the globe, the 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa illustrated worth of the oldest traditions of the [[Troupes de Marine|French Troop de Marine]].\n\n== Missions ==\n\nThe principal mission of the 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa, for which the brigade is apt to revolve around:\n\n* Amphibious actions: quick projection of a headquarter staff and one reinforced battalion (1,400 men) by naval amphibious [[French Navy|marine]] means, such as [[Mistral-class amphibious assault ship]].\n* Security missions, securitization of urbain oriented combat designated areas.\n* Deep decentralization action of search and reconnaissance oriented missions.\n* Rapid and deep incursions (armored raids, 100&nbsp;km range)\n\nThe 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa is present around the globe and also relieves missions of short duration such as in [[Senegal]], [[Guyana]] in Mayotte and [[Djibouti]]. The 9<sup>e</sup>BIMa actively participates to missions with the [[French Navy]] as the land terrestrial land component of Amphibious groups.\n\nThe 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa is twinned with [[Royal Marines|3rd Royal Marines Commando Brigade]] of the [[Royal Navy]]. Within this title, from 28 May to 1 June 2012, the center of amphibious operations of the headquarter staff embarked on [[Mistral (L9013)|BPC Mistral]] with the designated exercise Narval. 10 officers of the headquarter staff of the (twin brigade) participated in light of preparation to exercise Corsican Lion which took place from 17 October to 26 October 2012.\n\n== Organization 2016 ==\n\n[[File:9th Marine Brigade.png|thumb|9th Marine Infantry Brigade]]\n\n* 9{{sup|e}} Compagnie de Commandement et de Transmissions (9{{sup|e}} CCT) - Command and Signals Company in [[Poitiers]] with VAB\n* [[R\u00e9giment d'infanterie-chars de marine|R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie-Chars de Marine]] (RICM) - Armoured Marine Infantry Regiment (light cavalry) in [[Poitiers]] with [[AMX 10 RC]] and [[ERC 90 Sagaie|ERC 90]]\n* [[1st Marine Infantry Regiment|1{{sup|er}} R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie de Marine]] (1{{sup|er}} RIMa) - Armoured Marine Infantry Regiment (light cavalry) in [[Angoul\u00eame]] with [[AMX 10 RC]] and [[ERC 90 Sagaie|ERC 90]]\n* [[2nd Marine Infantry Regiment|2{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie de Marine]] (2{{sup|e}} RIMa) - Marine Infantry Regiment in [[Le Mans]] with [[V\u00e9hicule blind\u00e9 de combat d'infanterie|VBCI]]\n* [[3rd Marine Infantry Regiment|3{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie de Marine]] (3{{sup|e}} RIMa) - Marine Infantry Regiment in [[Vannes]] with [[V\u00e9hicule de l'Avant Blind\u00e9|VAB]]\n* [[126th Infantry Regiment (France)|126{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie]] (126{{sup|e}} RI) - Infantry Regiment in [[Brive-la-Gaillarde]] with VAB (will be the first unit to receive the new [[VBMR Griffon]] in 2018)\n* [[11th Marine Artillery Regiment|11{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment d'Artillerie de Marine]] (11{{sup|e}} RAMa) - Marine Artillery Regiment in [[Saint-Aubin-du-Cormier]]  with [[TRF1]] howitzers, [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer|CAESAR]] self-propelled howitzers and [[Mortier 120mm Ray\u00e9 Tract\u00e9 Mod\u00e8le F1|RTF1]] mortars\n* [[6th Engineer Regiment|6{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment du G\u00e9nie]] (6{{sup|e}} RG) - Engineer Regiment in [[Angers]]\n\n== Fanfare band ==\nThe brigade maintains a voluntary [[military band]] placed under the authority of the commanding general of the 9eBIMa. It was formed in the 1950s and then became the brigade band in July 2003. It was originally based in [[Dinan]] and then in [[Nantes]].<ref>https://m.lanouvellerepublique.fr/vienne%252Fcommune%252Fdange-saint-romain%252Ffanfare-et-bagad-de-la-9e-brigade-d-infanterie-de-marine-le-30-novembre</ref> It is the only voluntary army formation with a [[bagad]]. It is officially referred to as the ''Fanfare et bagad''. The band has been led since 1 September 2011 by Warrant Officer Fabrice Zeni.<ref>https://www.defense.gouv.fr/terre/bloc-patrimoine/musiques/fanfare-et-bagad-de-la-9e-brigade-d-infanterie-de-marine</ref> It operates ensmbles such as a ceremonial band and a [[big band]].\n\n== Brigade Commanders ==\n\n*2003 - 2005 : [[G\u00e9n\u00e9ral]] Jean-Paul Thonier\n*2005 - 2007 : G\u00e9n\u00e9ral [[Herv\u00e9 Charpentier]]\n*2007 - 2009 : G\u00e9n\u00e9ral \u00c9ric Bonnemaison\n*2009 - 2011 : G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Hogard\n*2011 - 2013 : [[Fran\u00e7ois Lecointre|G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Fran\u00e7ois Lecointre]] \n*2013 - 2015 : G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Vincent Guionie\n*2015 - 201x :: G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Fran\u00e7ois Labuze\n\n== See also ==\n*[[French Navy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.defense.gouv.fr/terre/presentation/organisation-des-forces/brigades/9e-brigade-d-infanterie-de-marine]\n* [http://www.defense.gouv.fr/terre/presentation/organisation-des-forces/brigades/9e-brigade-d-infanterie-de-marine Page consacr\u00e9e \u00e0 la 9e BIMa sur le site du Minist\u00e8re de la D\u00e9fense]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161120042111/http://www.fanfare-bagad-9bima.fr/ Site de la fanfare et du bagad de la 9]\n* [http://secretdefense.blogs.liberation.fr/defense/2009/05/dossier-lordre-de-bataille-de-larm%C3%A9e-de-terre-2.html L'ordre de bataille de l'arm\u00e9e de terre]\n{{French Army Divisions}}\n{{CFAT}}\n\n[[Category:Brigades of France]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Amphibious landing brigades]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=9th Marine Infantry Brigade\n|native_name=9{{sup|e}} Brigade d'Infanterie de Marine\n| image= 9e B.L.B.Ma.jpg\n|caption=Badge\n|dates= 1 July 1870 - ''present''\n|country=France\n|allegiance=\n|branch=[[French Army]]\n|type=[[Armour]]\n|role=[[Amphibious warfare]]\n|size= ~ 8,000 \n|command_structure=[[1st Armored Division (France)|1st Division]]\n|current_commander=\n|garrison=[[Poitiers]]\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=''Semper et Ubique'' (''[[Latin|La]]'')<br>''Toujours et Partout'' (''[[French language|Fr]]'')<br>''Always and All over'' (''[[English language|Eng]]'')\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n'''9th Colonial Infantry Division'''<br>\n[[World War II]]\n*[[Operation Dragoon]]\n[[Indochina War]]<br>\n'''9th Brigade'''<br>\n'''9th Marine Infantry Division'''<br>\n[[Lebanese Civil War]]\n*[[Multinational Force in Lebanon]]\n[[Gulf War]]<br>\n[[Bosnian War]]<br>\n'''9th Light Armoured Marine Brigade'''<br>\n'''9th Marine Infantry Brigade'''<br>\n[[Global War on Terrorism| Global War on Terrorism (2001\u2013present)]]\n|notable_commanders=\n|anniversaries=\n}}\n\nThe '''9{{sup|th}} Marine Infantry Brigade''' ({{lang-fr|9{{sup|e}} Brigade d'Infanterie de Marine, 9{{sup|e}} BIMa}}) is a light armoured, amphibious unit of the ''[[Troupes de marine]]'' of the [[French Army]].\n\nIn July 1963, the 9{{sup|e}} Brigade was created in [[Brittany]]. On 1 January 1976, the 9th Brigade became the 9th Marine Infantry Division (9{{sup|e}} division d'Infanterie de Marine, 9{{sup|e}} DIMa), attached to the land intervention force, then the [[Rapid Action Force (FAR)|Rapid Action Force]] from 1984. On 1 July 1999, the 9th Marine Infantry Division became the 9th Marine Light Armoured Brigade. On 1 January 2013, the unit was renamed and downsized to the 9th Marine Infantry Brigade ({{lang-fr|9{{sup|e}} Brigade d'Infanterie de Marine, 9{{sup|e}} BIMa}}).\n\n== Creation and different nominations ==\n\n* 1943 - 1947 : creation of the 9th Colonial Infantry Division ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:9e division d'infanterie coloniale|9e Division d'Infanterie Coloniale]], 9<sup>e</sup> D.I.C }})\n* 1963 - 1976 : designated as 9th Brigade ({{lang-fr|9<sup>e</sup> Brigade, 9<sup>e</sup>B }})\n* 1976 - 1999 : designated as 9th Marine Infantry Division ({{lang-fr|9<sup>e</sup> Division d'Infanterie de Marine, 9<sup>e</sup> D.I.Ma }})\n* 1999 - 2013 : designated as 9th Light Armoured Marine Brigade ({{lang-fr|9<sup>e</sup> Brigade L\u00e9g\u00e8re Blind\u00e9e de Marine, 9<sup>e</sup> B.L.B.Ma }})\n* 2013\u2013present : designated as '''9th Marine Infantry Brigade''' ({{lang-fr|9<sup>e</sup> Brigade d'Infanterie de Marine, 9<sup>e</sup> B.I.Ma }})\n\n== History ==\n[[File:9th Colonial Division landing Elba 16 June 1944.jpg|thumb|right|Landing French 9th Colonial Infantry Division troops during the invasion of Elba. 16 June 1944.]]\nThe division is heir to the [[Blue Division (Second French Empire)|Blue Division]] which fought during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870, in particular during the [[Battle of Bazeilles]] and the 9th Colonial Infantry Division, part of the [[Free French Forces]], which distinguished themselves in the apprehending of [[Elba]] in June 1944 and the [[Operation Dragoon|disembarking in Provence]] on 15 August of the same year. The Division then made way to [[Indochina]], where it was placed dormant (without being dissolved) in December 1947. The unit was reactivated in July 1963 in [[Brittany]] under the designation of 9th Brigade. On 1 January 1976, the division was baptized as 9th Marine Infantry Division 9<sup>e</sup> DIMa. Accordingly, the division was attached to the terrestrial intervention force, then the [[Rapid Action Force (France)|Rapid Action Force]] (FAR) since 1983. On 1 July 1999, the unit was restructured in a brigade and was designated as 9th Light Armoured Marine Brigade (BLBMa). On 1 January 2013, the brigade was named to the current designation as the '''9th Marine Infantry Brigade''' (9<sup>e</sup> BIMa).\n\nThe headquarter staff is stationed in [[Poitiers]] since 1 July 2010. The motto of the brigade is \u00ab Semper et Ulbique \u00bb, [[Latin]] for \u00ab Always and All over \u00bb.\n\nThe \u00ab 9th \u00bb illustrated capability on all exterior theatres of operations where [[France]] has been engaged since [[World War II]]: [[Indochina War|Indochina]], [[Lebanese Civil War|Lebanon]], [[Gulf War|Kuwait]], Macedonia, [[Kosovo]], [[Bosnian War|Bosnia]], [[Republic of Congo|Congo]], [[Tchad]], [[Ivory Coast]]. From October 2010 to May 2011, the Brigade armed essentially [[Brigade La Fayette]] in [[Afghanistan]] by projecting a headquarter staff ( composed 50% of Marines, Bigors, Marine sapeurs of the 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa) and the tactical interam groupment of Richelieu armed by the [[2nd Marine Infantry Regiment]] 2<sup>e</sup> RIMa. On January 2013, elements of the Brigade took part in [[Operation Serval]].\n\nIn all [[combat]] engagement theatres around the globe, the 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa illustrated worth of the oldest traditions of the [[Troupes de Marine|French Troop de Marine]].\n\n== Missions ==\n\nThe principal mission of the 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa, for which the brigade is apt to revolve around:\n\n* Amphibious actions: quick projection of a headquarter staff and one reinforced battalion (1,400 men) by naval amphibious [[French Navy|marine]] means, such as [[Mistral-class amphibious assault ship]].\n* Security missions, securitization of urbain oriented combat designated areas.\n* Deep decentralization action of search and reconnaissance oriented missions.\n* Rapid and deep incursions (armored raids, 100&nbsp;km range)\n\nThe 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa is present around the globe and also relieves missions of short duration such as in [[Senegal]], [[Guyana]] in Mayotte and [[Djibouti]]. The 9<sup>e</sup>BIMa actively participates to missions with the [[French Navy]] as the land terrestrial land component of Amphibious groups.\n\nThe 9<sup>e</sup> BIMa is twinned with [[Royal Marines|3rd Royal Marines Commando Brigade]] of the [[Royal Navy]]. Within this title, from 28 May to 1 June 2012, the center of amphibious operations of the headquarter staff embarked on [[Mistral (L9013)|BPC Mistral]] with the designated exercise Narval. 10 officers of the headquarter staff of the (twin brigade) participated in light of preparation to exercise Corsican Lion which took place from 17 October to 26 October 2012.\n\n== Organization 2016 ==\n\n[[File:9th Marine Brigade.png|thumb|9th Marine Infantry Brigade]]\n\n* 9{{sup|e}} Compagnie de Commandement et de Transmissions (9{{sup|e}} CCT) - Command and Signals Company in [[Poitiers]] with VAB\n* [[R\u00e9giment d'infanterie-chars de marine|R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie-Chars de Marine]] (RICM) - Armoured Marine Infantry Regiment (light cavalry) in [[Poitiers]] with [[AMX 10 RC]] and [[ERC 90 Sagaie|ERC 90]]\n* [[1st Marine Infantry Regiment|1{{sup|er}} R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie de Marine]] (1{{sup|er}} RIMa) - Armoured Marine Infantry Regiment (light cavalry) in [[Angoul\u00eame]] with [[AMX 10 RC]] and [[ERC 90 Sagaie|ERC 90]]\n* [[2nd Marine Infantry Regiment|2{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie de Marine]] (2{{sup|e}} RIMa) - Marine Infantry Regiment in [[Le Mans]] with [[V\u00e9hicule blind\u00e9 de combat d'infanterie|VBCI]]\n* [[3rd Marine Infantry Regiment|3{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie de Marine]] (3{{sup|e}} RIMa) - Marine Infantry Regiment in [[Vannes]] with [[V\u00e9hicule de l'Avant Blind\u00e9|VAB]]\n* [[126th Infantry Regiment (France)|126{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment d'Infanterie]] (126{{sup|e}} RI) - Infantry Regiment in [[Brive-la-Gaillarde]] with VAB (will be the first unit to receive the new [[VBMR Griffon]] in 2018)\n* [[11th Marine Artillery Regiment|11{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment d'Artillerie de Marine]] (11{{sup|e}} RAMa) - Marine Artillery Regiment in [[Saint-Aubin-du-Cormier]]  with [[TRF1]] howitzers, [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer|CAESAR]] self-propelled howitzers and [[Mortier 120mm Ray\u00e9 Tract\u00e9 Mod\u00e8le F1|RTF1]] mortars\n* [[6th Engineer Regiment|6{{sup|e}} R\u00e9giment du G\u00e9nie]] (6{{sup|e}} RG) - Engineer Regiment in [[Angers]]\n\n== Fanfare band ==\nThe brigade maintains a voluntary [[military band]] placed under the authority of the commanding general of the 9eBIMa. It was formed in the 1950s and then became the brigade band in July 2003. It was orginally based in [[Dinan]] and then in [[Nantes]].<ref>https://m.lanouvellerepublique.fr/vienne%252Fcommune%252Fdange-saint-romain%252Ffanfare-et-bagad-de-la-9e-brigade-d-infanterie-de-marine-le-30-novembre</ref> It is the only voluntary army formation with a [[bagad]]. It is officially referred to as the ''Fanfare et bagad''. The band has been led since 1 September 2011 by Warrant Officer Fabrice Zeni.<ref>https://www.defense.gouv.fr/terre/bloc-patrimoine/musiques/fanfare-et-bagad-de-la-9e-brigade-d-infanterie-de-marine</ref> It operates ensmebles such as a ceremonial band and a [[big band]].\n\n== Brigade Commanders ==\n\n*2003 - 2005 : [[G\u00e9n\u00e9ral]] Jean-Paul Thonier\n*2005 - 2007 : G\u00e9n\u00e9ral [[Herv\u00e9 Charpentier]]\n*2007 - 2009 : G\u00e9n\u00e9ral \u00c9ric Bonnemaison\n*2009 - 2011 : G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Hogard\n*2011 - 2013 : [[Fran\u00e7ois Lecointre|G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Fran\u00e7ois Lecointre]] \n*2013 - 2015 : G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Vincent Guionie\n*2015 - 201x :: G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Fran\u00e7ois Labuze\n\n== See also ==\n*[[French Navy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.defense.gouv.fr/terre/presentation/organisation-des-forces/brigades/9e-brigade-d-infanterie-de-marine]\n* [http://www.defense.gouv.fr/terre/presentation/organisation-des-forces/brigades/9e-brigade-d-infanterie-de-marine Page consacr\u00e9e \u00e0 la 9e BIMa sur le site du Minist\u00e8re de la D\u00e9fense]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161120042111/http://www.fanfare-bagad-9bima.fr/ Site de la fanfare et du bagad de la 9]\n* [http://secretdefense.blogs.liberation.fr/defense/2009/05/dossier-lordre-de-bataille-de-larm%C3%A9e-de-terre-2.html L'ordre de bataille de l'arm\u00e9e de terre]\n{{French Army Divisions}}\n{{CFAT}}\n\n[[Category:Brigades of France]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Amphibious landing brigades]]\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/9th_Marine_Infantry_Brigade"}
